WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:14.140 --> 00:00:15.440
&gt;&gt; John Haskell:
Hello, everybody.

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:19.200
Welcome to The Kluge Center
here at The Library of Congress.

00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:22.220
The Kluge Center is right
through those doors over here,

00:00:22.220 --> 00:00:25.880
where we have at The Kluge
Center scholars in residence

00:00:25.880 --> 00:00:29.310
at both the postdoctoral level,

00:00:29.310 --> 00:00:32.290
as well as more established
scholars, such as Ivan Krastev

00:00:32.290 --> 00:00:35.940
who is our Chairman of
the panel here today.

00:00:35.940 --> 00:00:39.130
I'm John Haskell, the
Director of The Kluge Center.

00:00:39.130 --> 00:00:42.410
This panel is part of
a series that we do

00:00:42.410 --> 00:00:46.260
that we call Conversations
on the State of Democracy,

00:00:46.260 --> 00:00:49.150
and we're very glad you're here.

00:00:49.150 --> 00:00:54.050
Avail yourself of the sodas
and the water and snacks,

00:00:54.050 --> 00:00:55.920
and I think we're in for
a very interesting panel.

00:00:55.920 --> 00:00:59.540
I'm going to tell you a little
bit about how Ivan fits in here.

00:00:59.540 --> 00:01:01.890
As you can see from
our materials,

00:01:01.890 --> 00:01:04.990
he's the Kissinger Chair
in International Relations

00:01:04.990 --> 00:01:06.730
and Foreign Policy here
at The Kluge Center.

00:01:06.730 --> 00:01:09.810
He is the seventeenth
holder of that position.

00:01:09.810 --> 00:01:13.180
The Kissinger Program
was originated by friends

00:01:13.180 --> 00:01:15.800
of Henry Kissinger back at the
beginning of The Kluge Center

00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:19.450
in 2000 and they endowed a
Chair for which we are grateful.

00:01:19.450 --> 00:01:23.270
If you don't have a sense,
I know many of you are here

00:01:23.270 --> 00:01:26.280
because you do have a
sense of Mr. Krastev

00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:29.750
and the other panelists,
but I want to make it clear

00:01:29.750 --> 00:01:31.730
that whenever I talk
about the fact

00:01:31.730 --> 00:01:35.040
that The Kluge Center has
Ivan here for a couple

00:01:35.040 --> 00:01:38.260
of months this year and a couple
more months next year people

00:01:38.260 --> 00:01:40.200
are impressed.

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:44.290
He is known as perhaps
the authority on populism

00:01:44.290 --> 00:01:49.610
and liberal democracy in Europe
and Russia, so he's here,

00:01:49.610 --> 00:01:51.000
he's set-up this panel,
and I'm just going

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:53.340
to tell you a little
bit more about him.

00:01:53.340 --> 00:01:56.540
He is the Chairman of the Center
for Liberal Studies in Sofia,

00:01:56.540 --> 00:01:59.960
Bulgaria and the permanent
Fellow of the Institute

00:01:59.960 --> 00:02:03.540
for Human Sciences, IWM, Vienna.

00:02:03.540 --> 00:02:07.830
Ivan is going to lead a
conversation with the panelists

00:02:07.830 --> 00:02:09.270
and then there'll
be an opportunity

00:02:09.270 --> 00:02:10.570
for questions from you.

00:02:10.570 --> 00:02:11.870
Take it away.

00:02:11.870 --> 00:02:13.610
&gt;&gt; Ivan Krastev:
Thank you very much.

00:02:13.610 --> 00:02:16.760
One of the most beautiful things

00:02:16.760 --> 00:02:20.690
that Kissinger has ever said
is he said when people say

00:02:20.690 --> 00:02:22.910
that they don't need
introduction don't do this

00:02:22.910 --> 00:02:25.220
to them because they
take part in these things

00:02:25.220 --> 00:02:27.840
for the pleasure of
being introduced.

00:02:27.840 --> 00:02:31.350
So, of course, I'm not
as kind of spectacular

00:02:31.350 --> 00:02:35.030
as this introduction was, but
it was a really great privilege

00:02:35.030 --> 00:02:38.160
to be here and only somebody
who has not been part

00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:43.360
of The Kluge Center doesn't
know how beautiful it is.

00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:45.970
The people that you see on the
panel and some of the people

00:02:45.970 --> 00:02:48.190
that you see in the room are
part of a strange project

00:02:48.190 --> 00:02:50.450
that we started two
or three years ago,

00:02:50.450 --> 00:02:52.610
and I'm basically going
to introduce it in order

00:02:52.610 --> 00:02:56.150
to understand why we're
here and what we are doing.

00:02:56.150 --> 00:02:59.930
There is a famous story
saying that the actor,

00:02:59.930 --> 00:03:05.420
the Hollywood kind of megastar,
Cary Grant, once was invited

00:03:05.420 --> 00:03:09.350
to a charity cocktail
in Hollywood,

00:03:09.350 --> 00:03:12.240
but he has forgotten
his invitation.

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:16.230
And there was this very
tough lady on the entrance,

00:03:16.230 --> 00:03:18.750
and he said I should enter,
where is your invitation?

00:03:18.750 --> 00:03:21.250
He said, sorry, I
have forgotten it,

00:03:21.250 --> 00:03:23.730
and she said, you cannot enter.

00:03:23.730 --> 00:03:26.800
And he said, but
I am Cary Grant.

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:31.420
And she looked at him and said,
you don't look like Cary Grant.

00:03:31.420 --> 00:03:34.460
And he said, nobody
looks like Cary Grant.

00:03:34.460 --> 00:03:37.670
Ah. And this is quite important
because when we started one

00:03:37.670 --> 00:03:39.510
of the things that we can
be very much interested

00:03:39.510 --> 00:03:43.730
in was there was all this
talk about liberal order.

00:03:43.730 --> 00:03:46.280
The liberal order never looked

00:03:46.280 --> 00:03:49.190
in the way basically this
course can be writing about it.

00:03:49.190 --> 00:03:51.390
Nobody looks like Cary Grant.

00:03:51.390 --> 00:03:55.430
But at the same time some years
ago when basically all the talk

00:03:55.430 --> 00:03:58.760
about the crisis of liberal
order started we figured

00:03:58.760 --> 00:04:01.480
out that this course on
the hypocrisy of the West

00:04:01.480 --> 00:04:04.220
on the wild side, but
also the Western discourse

00:04:04.220 --> 00:04:07.280
on the hypocrisy of
others is becoming the very

00:04:07.280 --> 00:04:08.890
central discourse.

00:04:08.890 --> 00:04:12.920
And what is quite important
is that attacking somebody

00:04:12.920 --> 00:04:16.790
for being hypocritical is
the way basically to attack

00:04:16.790 --> 00:04:19.590
without offering an alternative.

00:04:19.590 --> 00:04:21.650
You are attacking all the
time people for standing

00:04:21.650 --> 00:04:23.580
up to their own ideals or values

00:04:23.580 --> 00:04:25.900
so you don't need basically
to do anything else.

00:04:25.900 --> 00:04:29.270
So then the Center for Liberal
Strategy was a great support

00:04:29.270 --> 00:04:32.240
from the Robert Bush
Foundation, we decided to do one

00:04:32.240 --> 00:04:34.700
of those projects that
people are not doing anymore.

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:38.220
To connect the very
interesting group of people,

00:04:38.220 --> 00:04:42.380
a mixture of policymakers,
policy intellectuals, academics,

00:04:42.380 --> 00:04:46.500
and we decided to visit four
countries in which the discourse

00:04:46.500 --> 00:04:48.970
of hypocrisy is central

00:04:48.970 --> 00:04:52.520
to the way they comment
on foreign policy.

00:04:52.520 --> 00:04:55.040
Russia, basically
very much talking

00:04:55.040 --> 00:04:58.190
about the power revolutions
and to the native expansion.

00:04:58.190 --> 00:05:02.020
Turkey, very much
centering on the relations

00:05:02.020 --> 00:05:03.520
with the European Union.

00:05:03.520 --> 00:05:05.670
Iran, because of
the nuclear deal.

00:05:05.670 --> 00:05:08.010
And also being interested
in Greece

00:05:08.010 --> 00:05:10.620
because during the European
crisis there was a lot of talk

00:05:10.620 --> 00:05:14.930
about the bailout plan and was
basically Brussels hypocritical

00:05:14.930 --> 00:05:18.480
in the way it was
treating these countries.

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:22.130
On the other side, the West
itself was very much kind

00:05:22.130 --> 00:05:26.960
of unhappy with the hypocrisies
of the regimes which likes

00:05:26.960 --> 00:05:29.570
to talk like democracies,
so liberal order

00:05:29.570 --> 00:05:30.920
but at the same time
the deal was

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:33.850
that they had been
faking it all the time.

00:05:33.850 --> 00:05:38.020
So what we have been doing is
was a lot of serious meetings,

00:05:38.020 --> 00:05:42.400
but I'm talking about
meetings, 30, 40 people,

00:05:42.400 --> 00:05:45.080
and trying to cover the
whole political spectrum,

00:05:45.080 --> 00:05:48.260
members of government, both
Russia, Turkey around members

00:05:48.260 --> 00:05:51.450
of the opposition,
academic think tanks.

00:05:51.450 --> 00:05:54.700
And then we came here
because interestingly enough,

00:05:54.700 --> 00:05:57.600
nevertheless that people
basically can be very critical

00:05:57.600 --> 00:05:59.620
to what is happening
in the US when it comes

00:05:59.620 --> 00:06:01.680
to foreign policy
there is one thing

00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:05.200
that the current administration
cannot be accused of

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:07.150
and this is being hypocritical.

00:06:07.150 --> 00:06:11.140
In a certain way you
have a very strong talk

00:06:11.140 --> 00:06:15.050
about interests only, most of
the policies are not justified

00:06:15.050 --> 00:06:19.500
on a value level, and for
us the question was how much

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:21.030
words matter.

00:06:21.030 --> 00:06:23.410
And our starting assumption is

00:06:23.410 --> 00:06:26.390
that policy is not simply
what governments do,

00:06:26.390 --> 00:06:29.750
but also how they
justify their policies.

00:06:29.750 --> 00:06:32.510
And even one and the same
act of the government,

00:06:32.510 --> 00:06:36.110
being justified differently
is a different policy.

00:06:36.110 --> 00:06:39.700
And this for us was a trite
way basically to make sense

00:06:39.700 --> 00:06:41.370
of the transformation
of the world.

00:06:41.370 --> 00:06:43.330
So what we are going
to do, we're not going

00:06:43.330 --> 00:06:45.430
to present what is
interesting about this project,

00:06:45.430 --> 00:06:47.080
we're going to end
up with a report

00:06:47.080 --> 00:06:50.140
with much more interesting was
to keep the diversity of views.

00:06:50.140 --> 00:06:53.400
When we talk about the crisis
of liberal order we are going

00:06:53.400 --> 00:06:55.940
to present four different
points of view based

00:06:55.940 --> 00:06:58.720
on the four different
types of a crisis.

00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:01.650
In a certain way everybody
talks about the crisis

00:07:01.650 --> 00:07:03.800
of liberal order on
institutional level,

00:07:03.800 --> 00:07:06.590
value levels, but for every
person this is also the crisis

00:07:06.590 --> 00:07:08.710
of certain contacts
that you know best.

00:07:08.710 --> 00:07:11.050
So I'm going to start
with Robert Cooper,

00:07:11.050 --> 00:07:12.350
which is probably one

00:07:12.350 --> 00:07:16.010
of the most legendary
European diplomats and author,

00:07:16.010 --> 00:07:23.650
he wrote one of the classical
books of the self-understanding

00:07:23.650 --> 00:07:26.180
of the way the European Union
was working throughout the

00:07:26.180 --> 00:07:27.490
banking of nations.

00:07:27.490 --> 00:07:31.340
He has been the Foreign
Policy Advisor to Tommy Blair

00:07:31.340 --> 00:07:35.400
and that he left because he was
not supporting the war in Iraq

00:07:35.400 --> 00:07:37.630
and he was the Foreign
Policy Advisor

00:07:37.630 --> 00:07:39.360
to Javier Salona [assumed
spelling] and then

00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:40.660
to Crattie Ashton
[assumed spelling].

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:46.080
And from this point of view he
and his view of BREXIT is going

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:49.450
to be the first thing
of the way we are trying

00:07:49.450 --> 00:07:51.480
to introduce how
there is the kind

00:07:51.480 --> 00:07:55.440
of a local crisis we are
experiencing, what is changing.

00:07:55.440 --> 00:07:56.740
Robert?

00:07:56.740 --> 00:07:58.040
&gt;&gt; Robert Cooper: Right.

00:07:58.040 --> 00:07:59.340
Thank you.

00:07:59.340 --> 00:08:04.280
So I'm going to say a few words
about where BREXIT came from,

00:08:04.280 --> 00:08:09.000
about the referendum campaign
and about the consequence

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.600
of the UK leaving
the European Union

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:13.230
for the International Order.

00:08:13.230 --> 00:08:15.990
First of all, where
did it come from?

00:08:15.990 --> 00:08:19.650
Well, I'd be quite honest
because I'm not paid

00:08:19.650 --> 00:08:21.280
by anybody so I say what I like.

00:08:21.280 --> 00:08:24.610
It came from the
Conservative Party.

00:08:24.610 --> 00:08:28.490
Conservative Party had a
problem, it had a problem

00:08:28.490 --> 00:08:33.590
for a long time with
the European Union,

00:08:33.590 --> 00:08:35.890
and it became quite serious for
David Cameron [assumed spelling]

00:08:35.890 --> 00:08:42.320
and he decided to go above the
Party by having a referendum.

00:08:42.320 --> 00:08:46.870
Actually, Harold Wilson did the
same thing back in the 1970s

00:08:46.870 --> 00:08:48.240
with a different result.

00:08:48.240 --> 00:08:51.620
And so the Conservative
Party is a kind

00:08:51.620 --> 00:08:53.770
of institution in
long-term decline.

00:08:53.770 --> 00:08:55.350
It used to have three
million members

00:08:55.350 --> 00:08:57.960
and now it's somewhere
below 100,000,

00:08:57.960 --> 00:09:01.990
so it's actually a increasingly
pathetic organization,

00:09:01.990 --> 00:09:04.410
but it's one of the two
increasingly pathetic

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:08.330
organizations that runs
our country in Britain.

00:09:08.330 --> 00:09:10.940
And David Cameron used
to go around saying,

00:09:10.940 --> 00:09:16.560
the people of Britain are
demanding a say on Europe.

00:09:16.560 --> 00:09:22.590
Actually, the people of
Britain didn't care that much,

00:09:22.590 --> 00:09:25.210
they were interested in
education, in housing,

00:09:25.210 --> 00:09:28.880
they were wondering why their
salaries would remain static

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:30.310
whereas those of the bankers

00:09:30.310 --> 00:09:34.300
who had ruined the
country were racing ahead.

00:09:34.300 --> 00:09:36.510
They were wondering about
all those normal things,

00:09:36.510 --> 00:09:40.990
they weren't that problemed with
the European Union, however,

00:09:40.990 --> 00:09:42.930
they then held the
referendum campaign

00:09:42.930 --> 00:09:46.090
and everybody became bothered
with it and have never ceased

00:09:46.090 --> 00:09:47.390
to be bothered with
it ever since.

00:09:47.390 --> 00:09:52.740
It's the way in which you may
be friends when you start a war

00:09:52.740 --> 00:09:55.520
with a country, but by the
end of the war it's guaranteed

00:09:55.520 --> 00:09:56.820
that you've got enemies.

00:09:56.820 --> 00:10:02.380
And so the referendum
created the problem,

00:10:02.380 --> 00:10:05.530
it didn't solve the problem
for the Conservative Party,

00:10:05.530 --> 00:10:08.770
but it transferred the
problem to a higher level.

00:10:08.770 --> 00:10:12.110
And instead of ruining the
Conservative Party they decided

00:10:12.110 --> 00:10:15.680
to ruin the whole country.

00:10:15.680 --> 00:10:18.510
That's the kind of
proximate cause

00:10:18.510 --> 00:10:20.270
of the referendum
was the problem

00:10:20.270 --> 00:10:21.680
in the Conservative Party.

00:10:21.680 --> 00:10:24.880
The longer run cause
was a general failure

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:29.090
of the government and
all responsible people

00:10:29.090 --> 00:10:32.460
to explain the European
Union properly.

00:10:32.460 --> 00:10:38.310
Now it's very difficult, it
has become increasingly visible

00:10:38.310 --> 00:10:42.720
because this is a very
complicated gigantic

00:10:42.720 --> 00:10:45.710
in a way enterprise
and institution,

00:10:45.710 --> 00:10:50.310
and actually what's
happening now it makes clear

00:10:50.310 --> 00:10:52.920
that almost nobody
understands it completely.

00:10:52.920 --> 00:10:56.840
I worked there for 10 years and
I discover new things every day

00:10:56.840 --> 00:10:58.500
that I didn't know about it.

00:10:58.500 --> 00:11:03.330
About like, for example,
that if Britain leaves

00:11:03.330 --> 00:11:06.000
without an agreement
the airports will close

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:09.370
because no planes will have air
worthiness because they come

00:11:09.370 --> 00:11:10.690
from the European Union.

00:11:10.690 --> 00:11:13.630
Thousands of things
like that will stop.

00:11:13.630 --> 00:11:18.910
It's a sort of, it's hidden,
but it's much more important

00:11:18.910 --> 00:11:22.730
than anyone understands.

00:11:22.730 --> 00:11:26.520
So it was out of the
Conservative Party's problem

00:11:26.520 --> 00:11:27.820
and general ignorance.

00:11:27.820 --> 00:11:34.070
And then the referendum campaign
made extraordinarily good use

00:11:34.070 --> 00:11:36.200
of the ignorance, indeed,
it used the ignorance

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:38.990
by telling an enormous amount
of people wanted to leave,

00:11:38.990 --> 00:11:41.000
telling an enormous
amount of lies.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:44.510
Very direct, visible,
traceable lies,

00:11:44.510 --> 00:11:46.060
but they got away with them.

00:11:46.060 --> 00:11:48.210
Even government ministers
demonstrated

00:11:48.210 --> 00:11:50.250
that they didn't know
about the European Union,

00:11:50.250 --> 00:11:52.590
and people didn't know sort

00:11:52.590 --> 00:11:57.260
of as usual there was
an immigration element,

00:11:57.260 --> 00:11:58.560
what role is foreigner,

00:11:58.560 --> 00:12:02.570
particularly what role is
European foreigners doing here?

00:12:02.570 --> 00:12:04.200
And people thought
several things

00:12:04.200 --> 00:12:09.170
about the European immigrants,
and Britain is full of them,

00:12:09.170 --> 00:12:12.800
this makes London
much more colorful.

00:12:12.800 --> 00:12:18.920
They thought that these people
were responsible for the decline

00:12:18.920 --> 00:12:21.930
in the social services
because they were arriving

00:12:21.930 --> 00:12:24.460
and making use of
the social services,

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:25.800
which they hadn't paid for.

00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:29.540
It's not true, actually the
immigrants were mostly young

00:12:29.540 --> 00:12:31.210
people, they were healthy,

00:12:31.210 --> 00:12:33.150
they didn't use the
healthcare system,

00:12:33.150 --> 00:12:34.780
they were not contributors

00:12:34.780 --> 00:12:38.050
to the social services,
so that wasn't true.

00:12:38.050 --> 00:12:44.500
Another bit of ignorance,
you ask people in Britain

00:12:44.500 --> 00:12:47.080
where does foreign investment
come from in Britain?

00:12:47.080 --> 00:12:54.400
And they'll tell you, well,
about they say I think,

00:12:54.400 --> 00:12:58.440
they normally guess that
about 30% comes from the EU,

00:12:58.440 --> 00:13:03.750
that's a mistake, it's
actually 63% comes from the EU.

00:13:03.750 --> 00:13:08.230
They think about 30%
probably comes from the USA,

00:13:08.230 --> 00:13:10.770
that's wrong, it's actually 17%.

00:13:10.770 --> 00:13:15.860
They think that --
no, sorry, it's 23% --

00:13:15.860 --> 00:13:21.310
they think that 17% comes from
China, the answer is it's less

00:13:21.310 --> 00:13:23.170
than 1% comes from China.

00:13:23.170 --> 00:13:28.640
Overwhelmingly investment in
Britain that's foreign comes

00:13:28.640 --> 00:13:34.190
from the EU, and that
means that supply chains go

00:13:34.190 --> 00:13:38.060
across national boundaries,
having no customs controls

00:13:38.060 --> 00:13:40.300
and things like that, having
completely open market

00:13:40.300 --> 00:13:43.150
for the EU is absolutely
essential

00:13:43.150 --> 00:13:44.670
for the British economy.

00:13:44.670 --> 00:13:52.850
So the campaign was
full of lies.

00:13:52.850 --> 00:13:56.180
And the campaign also took
place at a rather unlucky moment

00:13:56.180 --> 00:13:58.480
because of complaints
about immigration,

00:13:58.480 --> 00:14:03.050
which were mostly not
justified, but this took place

00:14:03.050 --> 00:14:07.090
at the moment when there was
a vast migration crisis going

00:14:07.090 --> 00:14:09.780
on in the eastern Mediterranean

00:14:09.780 --> 00:14:12.530
as a consequence
of the Syrian war.

00:14:12.530 --> 00:14:15.710
Migration crisis was nowhere
near Europe, but it was all

00:14:15.710 --> 00:14:18.630
over the TV screens, so that
was another bit of bad luck.

00:14:18.630 --> 00:14:21.060
And then there was a bit
of sloppiness on the part

00:14:21.060 --> 00:14:23.040
of the government in the way

00:14:23.040 --> 00:14:25.010
in which the referendum
was organized,

00:14:25.010 --> 00:14:26.470
but I leave that aside.

00:14:26.470 --> 00:14:28.790
Now what about the
consequences of BREXIT?

00:14:28.790 --> 00:14:31.820
Assuming if it's going to
happen, I assume that it's going

00:14:31.820 --> 00:14:35.400
to happen, although I'm
not absolutely certain

00:14:35.400 --> 00:14:39.090
because I had never seen
such chaos in Britain before.

00:14:39.090 --> 00:14:43.160
Anything is possible at the
moment, but the likely result is

00:14:43.160 --> 00:14:48.660
that the UK leaves, that will
leave the UK isolated, weakened,

00:14:48.660 --> 00:14:52.520
impoverished, but actually
is bad for the liberal order

00:14:52.520 --> 00:14:54.010
because the UK is
a liberal country

00:14:54.010 --> 00:14:58.090
and it's played a useful
role in what I think

00:14:58.090 --> 00:15:01.270
of as the liberal order,
which is essentially NATO

00:15:01.270 --> 00:15:03.590
and the European Union
and then you've got one

00:15:03.590 --> 00:15:07.180
or two slightly less
important add-ons, like the IMF

00:15:07.180 --> 00:15:10.610
and the WPO and the UN, which
doesn't function that well,

00:15:10.610 --> 00:15:17.240
but basically the West
is the liberal order.

00:15:17.240 --> 00:15:19.200
And the UK isolated, angry,

00:15:19.200 --> 00:15:22.240
quarreling with its
neighbors is not a good thing

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:23.540
for liberal order.

00:15:23.540 --> 00:15:26.470
And then a final remark on
what is the liberal order?

00:15:26.470 --> 00:15:27.770
I think another definition

00:15:27.770 --> 00:15:29.870
for the liberal order is
it's what's brought us peace

00:15:29.870 --> 00:15:35.000
for 70 years in all
kinds of different forms.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:40.620
NATO, and when I think of NATO
bringing peace I'm thinking

00:15:40.620 --> 00:15:45.060
of the cold war, but not just of
the cold war, peace between East

00:15:45.060 --> 00:15:48.580
and West, I'm thinking
of peace within Europe.

00:15:48.580 --> 00:15:56.560
The fact that before NATO
every country in Europe looked

00:15:56.560 --> 00:16:00.240
at their military and
compared it with the military

00:16:00.240 --> 00:16:02.390
of their neighbor,
and Britain used

00:16:02.390 --> 00:16:05.220
to run something called
the two Navy standard.

00:16:05.220 --> 00:16:09.140
We wanted to have a
Navy that was equal

00:16:09.140 --> 00:16:10.980
to the next two countries.

00:16:10.980 --> 00:16:14.360
Sometime the end of the 19th
Century we stopped counting the

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:16.950
USA because we knew
we couldn't compete,

00:16:16.950 --> 00:16:20.170
but so everybody compared
themselves to their neighbors.

00:16:20.170 --> 00:16:23.610
Under NATO nobody does
that unless they complain

00:16:23.610 --> 00:16:27.200
about the Germans not
spending enough on defense.

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:30.770
So NATO is a powerful part
of what has brought peace

00:16:30.770 --> 00:16:33.370
for 70 years and
the European Union.

00:16:33.370 --> 00:16:37.360
There are two ways of
making, of having peace.

00:16:37.360 --> 00:16:40.800
One is to be very powerful,
balance of power to the left.

00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:43.130
The other is to have
good political relations

00:16:43.130 --> 00:16:44.430
with your neighbors.

00:16:44.430 --> 00:16:46.430
And the European
Union is intended

00:16:46.430 --> 00:16:48.910
and systematically does that.

00:16:48.910 --> 00:16:51.590
Now people will tell
you today, well, peace,

00:16:51.590 --> 00:16:54.600
who cares, that's all old hat.

00:16:54.600 --> 00:16:58.830
Now I was sort of
brought up with Joan Baez,

00:16:58.830 --> 00:17:05.230
so I take this more seriously,
but actually what people

00:17:05.230 --> 00:17:12.300
in Britain forget is that we had
a low intensity war which went

00:17:12.300 --> 00:17:16.480
on for 20 years or
more in Ireland

00:17:16.480 --> 00:17:17.950
and we do have a land border.

00:17:17.950 --> 00:17:20.780
We think we're an island, but
we don't, we have a land border

00:17:20.780 --> 00:17:23.070
with the Republic of Ireland.

00:17:23.070 --> 00:17:25.550
And a condition of
the peace settlement

00:17:25.550 --> 00:17:31.040
in Ireland is called the Good
Friday Agreement by most of us

00:17:31.040 --> 00:17:34.290
and in Northern Ireland
called the Belfast Agreement,

00:17:34.290 --> 00:17:37.790
always a bad sign that when
they have different names

00:17:37.790 --> 00:17:39.220
for the same thing.

00:17:39.220 --> 00:17:44.390
But the background condition
of that was membership

00:17:44.390 --> 00:17:47.150
of the European Union, that
you didn't need to have,

00:17:47.150 --> 00:17:50.880
on the one hand that you didn't
need to have a border in Ireland

00:17:50.880 --> 00:17:53.550
so that those who
wished to could live

00:17:53.550 --> 00:17:58.490
in the united Ireland as,
indeed, in morph if you wished

00:17:58.490 --> 00:18:02.090
to you could have a
Republic of Ireland passport,

00:18:02.090 --> 00:18:05.180
but that's very important.

00:18:05.180 --> 00:18:08.590
And I can develop
a scenario in which

00:18:08.590 --> 00:18:13.910
if you recreate the border you
can recreate what they called

00:18:13.910 --> 00:18:16.960
the troubles, but which was
actually a low intensity war.

00:18:16.960 --> 00:18:18.390
It's perfectly possible.

00:18:18.390 --> 00:18:23.610
the second way in which the
European Union helped end the

00:18:23.610 --> 00:18:29.990
war in Ireland was it put Dublin
and London for the first time

00:18:29.990 --> 00:18:35.050
in a community together where
they cooperated and dealt

00:18:35.050 --> 00:18:37.870
with each other not as
a former colonial power,

00:18:37.870 --> 00:18:42.860
the former colonial
victim, but as equals

00:18:42.860 --> 00:18:45.980
and that was also
essential in the Irish peace.

00:18:45.980 --> 00:18:49.600
So when people tell you the
European Union is a peace

00:18:49.600 --> 00:18:54.200
project it's not nonsense, and
the weird thing is that Britain,

00:18:54.200 --> 00:18:58.210
which is a primary beneficiary
of this, hasn't noticed it

00:18:58.210 --> 00:19:00.320
until now, they still
don't understand it.

00:19:00.320 --> 00:19:04.580
They, I refer to my fellow
countrymen, I should say.

00:19:04.580 --> 00:19:06.910
so that's, I'm sorry,
there's much more to say

00:19:06.910 --> 00:19:08.210
and I've gone too far.

00:19:08.210 --> 00:19:09.510
&gt;&gt; Ivan Krastev:
Thank you very much.

00:19:09.510 --> 00:19:11.660
I was listening, and if I
remember rightly during the 20th

00:19:11.660 --> 00:19:14.030
Century there is only one year

00:19:14.030 --> 00:19:18.380
in which a British soldier
has not been killed in a small

00:19:18.380 --> 00:19:21.500
or a big war outside of the
territory of the United Kingdom.

00:19:21.500 --> 00:19:24.080
And, by the way,
this year is 1968.

00:19:24.080 --> 00:19:30.900
But from Britain we are going
to move to the United States.

00:19:30.900 --> 00:19:33.750
And for most of us coming here
and we had a lot of meetings

00:19:33.750 --> 00:19:35.180
for the last three days,

00:19:35.180 --> 00:19:38.950
the biggest problem is you
have two kinds of schools

00:19:38.950 --> 00:19:40.250
of thoughts in Europe today.

00:19:40.250 --> 00:19:42.960
There are people who are seeing
the changes in the United States

00:19:42.960 --> 00:19:48.080
as kind of a car accident,
something happened,

00:19:48.080 --> 00:19:51.690
there was a major kind
of accident in 2016,

00:19:51.690 --> 00:19:54.570
but they are going to
return back to the normal

00:19:54.570 --> 00:19:58.210
so we should wait for four,
eight, I don't know, 12 years

00:19:58.210 --> 00:20:01.040
and then basically everything
is going to be the way it was.

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:06.800
And there was a people who
said, and I'm much closer

00:20:06.800 --> 00:20:09.730
to this school, is that the
current President didn't create

00:20:09.730 --> 00:20:12.730
the wave, he's surfing on it.

00:20:12.730 --> 00:20:14.210
There was a major
transformation,

00:20:14.210 --> 00:20:17.020
there was a certain type of
a foreign policy consensus

00:20:17.020 --> 00:20:19.900
that did not fit to the
public consensus there,

00:20:19.900 --> 00:20:22.050
there are certain changes
that are going to survive,

00:20:22.050 --> 00:20:24.070
nevertheless, of who is
going to come to power.

00:20:24.070 --> 00:20:26.970
And from this point
of view for us one

00:20:26.970 --> 00:20:29.470
of the most interesting
questions was what are these

00:20:29.470 --> 00:20:32.710
changes, what are the
emerging consensuses

00:20:32.710 --> 00:20:36.040
of the way the United States now
views the world, keeping close

00:20:36.040 --> 00:20:37.720
with the fact that
it's not simply

00:20:37.720 --> 00:20:39.680
about American foreign
policy but also

00:20:39.680 --> 00:20:42.650
about very much polarized
domestic political space.

00:20:42.650 --> 00:20:46.720
And now I'll go to Rosa
Brooks here basically

00:20:46.720 --> 00:20:51.060
to give her take
and how she sees it.

00:20:51.060 --> 00:20:54.140
&gt;&gt; Rosa Brooks: Goodness,
that's a tough task,

00:20:54.140 --> 00:20:59.090
explaining American
politics and foreign policy.

00:20:59.090 --> 00:21:07.830
So, as Ivan said, this project
is about hypocrisy and the role,

00:21:07.830 --> 00:21:11.230
negative and maybe
positive, that hypocrisy plays

00:21:11.230 --> 00:21:15.070
in the discourse about the
liberal international order.

00:21:15.070 --> 00:21:17.290
And maybe I should
just start by saying

00:21:17.290 --> 00:21:19.990
that not only is Donald
Trump not a hypocrite,

00:21:19.990 --> 00:21:23.620
he may be many things, right, he
may be lying, he may be corrupt,

00:21:23.620 --> 00:21:28.800
he may care only about his own
interests, but partly for all

00:21:28.800 --> 00:21:30.740
of those reasons it's hard
to call him a hypocrite.

00:21:30.740 --> 00:21:34.360
He doesn't pretend to be
anything other than what he is.

00:21:34.360 --> 00:21:35.900
I think the American people

00:21:35.900 --> 00:21:40.030
and American policymakers are
also really hypocritical insofar

00:21:40.030 --> 00:21:45.760
as hypocrisy implies, charges
of hypocrisy imply a level

00:21:45.760 --> 00:21:52.120
of self-awareness and a
willingness to blink your eye

00:21:52.120 --> 00:21:55.390
at contradictions and
self-serving behavior.

00:21:55.390 --> 00:21:59.670
I think that the flaw in
American foreign policy and,

00:21:59.670 --> 00:22:02.030
indeed, American
internal politics is

00:22:02.030 --> 00:22:04.110
that we are entirely capable

00:22:04.110 --> 00:22:06.860
of fully believing multiple
contradictory things at once

00:22:06.860 --> 00:22:10.210
and we tend to truly believe
all the contradictory things.

00:22:10.210 --> 00:22:11.850
I think that when it comes

00:22:11.850 --> 00:22:16.070
to both the liberal
international order, itself,

00:22:16.070 --> 00:22:19.910
and when it comes to
Americans' understandings

00:22:19.910 --> 00:22:24.430
of our own country and our own
politics there are these central

00:22:24.430 --> 00:22:27.460
contradictions in it that
we have never resolved

00:22:27.460 --> 00:22:32.740
and we have lived for 70
plus years telling ourselves

00:22:32.740 --> 00:22:34.640
that perhaps we don't have
to resolve them and trying

00:22:34.640 --> 00:22:35.940
to pretend that they
don't exist.

00:22:35.940 --> 00:22:38.050
And here's what they
are, let me start

00:22:38.050 --> 00:22:40.330
with the so-called liberal
international order, right?

00:22:40.330 --> 00:22:42.790
Think about the contradictions
that are at the heart

00:22:42.790 --> 00:22:47.390
of the UN charter system that
emerges after World War II.

00:22:47.390 --> 00:22:51.580
We have on the one
hand a profound

00:22:51.580 --> 00:22:54.760
and quite revolutionary
commitment to the idea

00:22:54.760 --> 00:23:01.550
of universal rights, universal
rights possessed by individuals,

00:23:01.550 --> 00:23:06.860
not by virtue of their belonging
to a particular state or group,

00:23:06.860 --> 00:23:09.770
but simply by virtue
of being human.

00:23:09.770 --> 00:23:14.150
And from that notion of
individual human rights,

00:23:14.150 --> 00:23:17.400
universal human rights that
everyone possesses simply

00:23:17.400 --> 00:23:22.430
because they're human we get the
notion of self-determination,

00:23:22.430 --> 00:23:24.120
which is of course an extension

00:23:24.120 --> 00:23:26.550
of the deeply American
commitment

00:23:26.550 --> 00:23:30.980
to democratic governance,
that individuals,

00:23:30.980 --> 00:23:33.870
that governments have
legitimacy only insofar

00:23:33.870 --> 00:23:37.360
as they rest upon the
consent of the individuals

00:23:37.360 --> 00:23:38.680
that they are governing.

00:23:38.680 --> 00:23:41.900
So we have this commitment
to individual rights,

00:23:41.900 --> 00:23:47.150
which leads us to commitment to
self-determination and arguably

00:23:47.150 --> 00:23:50.340
to democratic forms
of governance and

00:23:50.340 --> 00:23:53.220
yet at the same time of
course the UN charter, itself,

00:23:53.220 --> 00:23:57.660
enshrines a commitment to
maintaining the status quo,

00:23:57.660 --> 00:24:01.070
the post-World War II status
quo in all kinds of ways,

00:24:01.070 --> 00:24:05.620
including maintaining the
states that emerge out of that,

00:24:05.620 --> 00:24:08.930
maintaining the power
structure that emerges

00:24:08.930 --> 00:24:10.920
out of World War II,
specifically looking

00:24:10.920 --> 00:24:14.040
at the permanent members
of the UN Security Council

00:24:14.040 --> 00:24:17.680
with their veto power and
so forth, and a commitment

00:24:17.680 --> 00:24:21.410
to non-interference,
to non-intervention

00:24:21.410 --> 00:24:24.910
that says states do not
get to and are prohibited

00:24:24.910 --> 00:24:29.560
from intervening in the
internal affairs of one another.

00:24:29.560 --> 00:24:31.850
So that's, and the trouble is

00:24:31.850 --> 00:24:35.980
of course those two things don't
actually fit very well together.

00:24:35.980 --> 00:24:40.390
If you posit that
individuals have rights

00:24:40.390 --> 00:24:45.180
to self-determination and to
free expression and to all sorts

00:24:45.180 --> 00:24:47.920
of other things and
you posit that states

00:24:47.920 --> 00:24:50.700
and international organizations,
such as the United Nations,

00:24:50.700 --> 00:24:54.770
have a responsibility to
protect and defend the rights

00:24:54.770 --> 00:24:58.380
of individuals and the
aspirations of peoples,

00:24:58.380 --> 00:25:01.970
and then you also say, oh, but
by the way you can't interfere

00:25:01.970 --> 00:25:05.010
in the status quo and by
the way a system which says

00:25:05.010 --> 00:25:07.760
that five states have
permanent veto power

00:25:07.760 --> 00:25:09.390
in the Security Council not

00:25:09.390 --> 00:25:12.480
because a democracy
chose those states,

00:25:12.480 --> 00:25:14.550
not because they have the
majority of the people,

00:25:14.550 --> 00:25:17.600
but simply because,
because, just because.

00:25:17.600 --> 00:25:21.290
You can't sustain that,
there's no possible way

00:25:21.290 --> 00:25:24.790
to square those things
completely, and so you have

00:25:24.790 --> 00:25:28.530
to either pretend the
contradiction doesn't exist,

00:25:28.530 --> 00:25:31.550
or in contrast to
hypocrisy I think, as I said,

00:25:31.550 --> 00:25:33.720
the American failing
is to manage

00:25:33.720 --> 00:25:36.590
to maintain a very high
level of cognitive dissonance

00:25:36.590 --> 00:25:39.010
in which you just have
two separate little boxes

00:25:39.010 --> 00:25:40.310
in your head.

00:25:40.310 --> 00:25:42.590
You have one box that says
commitment to individual rights

00:25:42.590 --> 00:25:45.740
and self-determination and
democracy, and another box

00:25:45.740 --> 00:25:48.710
that is a much more realist
kind of box, you know,

00:25:48.710 --> 00:25:50.280
in international relations terms

00:25:50.280 --> 00:25:54.100
that box says leave well
enough alone, power matters,

00:25:54.100 --> 00:25:57.250
historical structure matters,

00:25:57.250 --> 00:26:01.960
sorry stability trumps
individual rights

00:26:01.960 --> 00:26:05.670
and universalist aspirations
all the time and you have

00:26:05.670 --> 00:26:07.690
to keep those in
two separate boxes.

00:26:07.690 --> 00:26:09.530
And so when you're talking
about one you mean it,

00:26:09.530 --> 00:26:11.480
and when you're talking
about the other you mean it,

00:26:11.480 --> 00:26:16.520
and if you're American you
keep those boxes so separate

00:26:16.520 --> 00:26:17.820
that you don't actually have

00:26:17.820 --> 00:26:19.200
to be confronted
with the difference.

00:26:19.200 --> 00:26:21.750
If you're not American you're
far more inclined to say, hey,

00:26:21.750 --> 00:26:25.220
wait a second, you know, hold
on, how can you believe both

00:26:25.220 --> 00:26:26.550
of those things at once?

00:26:26.550 --> 00:26:28.770
To which the answer is that
again unless you're very good

00:26:28.770 --> 00:26:31.970
at cognitive dissonance you
can't, and I think the roots

00:26:31.970 --> 00:26:36.230
that tension gives rise around
the globe to a tremendous amount

00:26:36.230 --> 00:26:40.110
of anger, to charges
of hypocrisy and so on.

00:26:40.110 --> 00:26:43.480
When it comes to
American internal politics

00:26:43.480 --> 00:26:47.360
in many ways we remain a country
that ourselves are sort of torn

00:26:47.360 --> 00:26:48.780
between those two impulses,

00:26:48.780 --> 00:26:52.320
the impulse towards saying
every individual matters,

00:26:52.320 --> 00:26:55.850
it's individual rights that
matter, and the impulse to say,

00:26:55.850 --> 00:26:58.340
no, it's power and
concentrations of power

00:26:58.340 --> 00:27:00.980
that matter more and
stability matters more.

00:27:00.980 --> 00:27:03.880
And I think that in some ways
when we look at the election

00:27:03.880 --> 00:27:05.800
of 2016, when we
look at what's going

00:27:05.800 --> 00:27:09.390
on in the US right now we're
very much seeing a conflict

00:27:09.390 --> 00:27:12.930
between a vision of
America that is very much

00:27:12.930 --> 00:27:18.010
about the protection of rights
and universalist principles

00:27:18.010 --> 00:27:22.080
versus a discourse that says,
nope, nope, it's about power,

00:27:22.080 --> 00:27:24.940
it's about stability, it's about
protecting the prerogatives

00:27:24.940 --> 00:27:28.470
of those who either hold power
and want to keep it or used

00:27:28.470 --> 00:27:30.400
to hold power, have
recently lost it

00:27:30.400 --> 00:27:33.370
and would like to have it back.

00:27:33.370 --> 00:27:37.900
And I do think that a lot of
the support for the election

00:27:37.900 --> 00:27:41.680
of President Trump has come
from that sort of second,

00:27:41.680 --> 00:27:45.090
that latter group, who are
saying it's about power

00:27:45.090 --> 00:27:46.660
and who keeps it
and whether those

00:27:46.660 --> 00:27:49.800
who lost it recently
can get it back again.

00:27:49.800 --> 00:27:52.570
There, too, you know I
don't think it's so much

00:27:52.570 --> 00:27:56.270
about hypocrisy, but it's
about these competing visions

00:27:56.270 --> 00:27:59.770
which most of us would
deny that we have,

00:27:59.770 --> 00:28:02.680
and we deny that we have them,
we deny that they're competing.

00:28:02.680 --> 00:28:04.770
But I do think that they --

00:28:04.770 --> 00:28:06.890
I'm not terribly
optimistic I should say

00:28:06.890 --> 00:28:09.990
about either the US politics --

00:28:09.990 --> 00:28:14.770
Ivan, you asked whether will
we revert to normal here

00:28:14.770 --> 00:28:19.050
in the United States, will
this moment be a blip, you know

00:28:19.050 --> 00:28:22.000
and in two years or in six years
we say, oh, well, that was kind

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:25.400
of strange but that's over
now, we go back to usual both

00:28:25.400 --> 00:28:28.920
in the United States and
in terms of the UK figures

00:28:28.920 --> 00:28:32.340
out the whole BREXIT thing,
we all revert to normal?

00:28:32.340 --> 00:28:35.630
I doubt it, I think
it's not impossible

00:28:35.630 --> 00:28:37.230
that that could happen,

00:28:37.230 --> 00:28:40.360
that everyone could just agree
let's just delete the last four

00:28:40.360 --> 00:28:41.660
years, six years, eight years,

00:28:41.660 --> 00:28:43.530
whatever it will
have been by then.

00:28:43.530 --> 00:28:48.720
I think unfortunately somewhat
more likely, not inevitable

00:28:48.720 --> 00:28:52.970
but more likely is that both
the international liberal order

00:28:52.970 --> 00:28:57.950
and the American, the
particularly American experiment

00:28:57.950 --> 00:29:03.200
in late empire democracy
both essentially crumble due

00:29:03.200 --> 00:29:05.560
to their own internal
contradictions.

00:29:05.560 --> 00:29:08.970
What comes after if
the American experiment

00:29:08.970 --> 00:29:11.500
in the liberal international
order crumble?

00:29:11.500 --> 00:29:13.610
I don't think it's
anything very good, right?

00:29:13.610 --> 00:29:16.400
I don't see anybody kind of
waiting in the wings saying,

00:29:16.400 --> 00:29:18.530
hey, we've got the
next great idea.

00:29:18.530 --> 00:29:22.060
I think that we are probably
due, unfortunately both

00:29:22.060 --> 00:29:26.170
in this country and globally,
for one of those periods

00:29:26.170 --> 00:29:30.050
that could last three or four
years and could last decades

00:29:30.050 --> 00:29:37.130
or even centuries of back to
power politics, back to power

00:29:37.130 --> 00:29:40.690
and force as primary means
of resolving disputes,

00:29:40.690 --> 00:29:44.900
and it's not going to be,
it's not an era I feel good

00:29:44.900 --> 00:29:46.990
about leaving to my children
and my grandchildren,

00:29:46.990 --> 00:29:50.590
but that's I think the direction
in which we're heading.

00:29:50.590 --> 00:29:51.890
&gt;&gt; Ivan Krastev:
Thank you very much.

00:29:51.890 --> 00:29:53.190
And, of course, Rosa
knows something

00:29:53.190 --> 00:29:57.510
about this contradiction
because she's a famous,

00:29:57.510 --> 00:30:00.650
also humorized professor,
who served in the Pentagon,

00:30:00.650 --> 00:30:03.290
so she knows both worlds.

00:30:03.290 --> 00:30:06.540
But one of the things which for
us was quite interesting was

00:30:06.540 --> 00:30:10.310
that people automatically
believed that the return

00:30:10.310 --> 00:30:13.890
to great power politics
is a return to realism,

00:30:13.890 --> 00:30:16.800
and this is something that
I'm personally questioning

00:30:16.800 --> 00:30:18.360
and this is what
not you're seeing.

00:30:18.360 --> 00:30:22.220
This is in a way identity type
of a great power politics.

00:30:22.220 --> 00:30:23.520
And Steven Walt [assumed
spelling],

00:30:23.520 --> 00:30:26.800
one of the famous realists,
was part of the group.

00:30:26.800 --> 00:30:31.300
It is one thing with this type
of a highly politicized and kind

00:30:31.300 --> 00:30:35.440
of changing the way
nation interest is defined.

00:30:35.440 --> 00:30:39.160
This very rational realism
view of foreign policy

00:30:39.160 --> 00:30:41.660
in such a way it does
not look very convincing.

00:30:41.660 --> 00:30:42.960
But Thomas Baggett
[assumed spelling],

00:30:42.960 --> 00:30:45.100
who is the Foreign Policy
Advisor to the German President

00:30:45.100 --> 00:30:49.190
and who is probably one of the
best known public intellectuals

00:30:49.190 --> 00:30:51.190
in Germany when it
comes to foreign policy,

00:30:51.190 --> 00:30:54.060
recently he said the end of
history was an American idea,

00:30:54.060 --> 00:30:57.630
but European reality and
particularly German reality.

00:30:57.630 --> 00:31:01.160
And I'm going to say why
for Europeans this talk

00:31:01.160 --> 00:31:03.070
about the change of
language appeared

00:31:03.070 --> 00:31:05.840
to be much more important
than to anybody else.

00:31:05.840 --> 00:31:08.090
For the United States,
for Russia, for China,

00:31:08.090 --> 00:31:13.300
for Turkey moving for a much
more liberal values colored

00:31:13.300 --> 00:31:16.330
justification of
government acts.

00:31:16.330 --> 00:31:18.900
It is a problem of choice.

00:31:18.900 --> 00:31:21.420
European Union cannot
easily shift

00:31:21.420 --> 00:31:25.840
to the national interest type of
justification of its policies.

00:31:25.840 --> 00:31:28.110
It's not a nation state.

00:31:28.110 --> 00:31:30.920
And, by the way, if you
see the nation states some

00:31:30.920 --> 00:31:32.680
of these nation states
are very small.

00:31:32.680 --> 00:31:35.710
I can easily understand
what it means for China

00:31:35.710 --> 00:31:38.610
or for the United States
becoming protection is

00:31:38.610 --> 00:31:40.650
nationalistic, but
you try to explain

00:31:40.650 --> 00:31:44.500
to me how Bulgaria is going
to benefit from the world

00:31:44.500 --> 00:31:46.780
in which everybody
goes this way.

00:31:46.780 --> 00:31:50.650
And from this point of view in
a certain way the German dilemma

00:31:50.650 --> 00:31:55.210
and the problem that Germany is
facing as a leading member state

00:31:55.210 --> 00:31:58.640
in my view is one of the most
interesting, but also one

00:31:58.640 --> 00:31:59.940
of the most challenging.

00:31:59.940 --> 00:32:02.110
So, Thomas?

00:32:02.110 --> 00:32:04.030
&gt;&gt; Thomas Bagger: Yes, thank
you, Ivan, and thank you

00:32:04.030 --> 00:32:07.370
to all of you for coming.

00:32:07.370 --> 00:32:12.120
I think, you know, when I
look back at the last 25,

00:32:12.120 --> 00:32:15.630
30 years since the end of
the fall of, since the fall

00:32:15.630 --> 00:32:19.770
of the wall, the end of the
cold war, which happened sort

00:32:19.770 --> 00:32:29.600
of at half point in my life,
this was the most surprising,

00:32:29.600 --> 00:32:34.490
the most unthinkable event
that I could possibly remember.

00:32:34.490 --> 00:32:39.520
And I was in a US university
computer lab in College Park,

00:32:39.520 --> 00:32:42.860
not very far from here, and
did my Masters Degree there

00:32:42.860 --> 00:32:46.090
and this was sort of
before laptop time.

00:32:46.090 --> 00:32:48.460
So we sat at this computer lab

00:32:48.460 --> 00:32:51.110
and there were American students
coming in and they're saying,

00:32:51.110 --> 00:32:53.690
telling and sort of saying
they're taking the wall down,

00:32:53.690 --> 00:32:55.770
they're taking the wall down.

00:32:55.770 --> 00:32:59.680
And I thought they must
have gotten something wrong,

00:32:59.680 --> 00:33:01.680
which wall are they
talking about?

00:33:01.680 --> 00:33:05.560
Because even with all
the runup to November 9,

00:33:05.560 --> 00:33:12.890
1989 it was out of my
imagination as a 24 year old

00:33:12.890 --> 00:33:14.850
that this could actually
happen and be true.

00:33:14.850 --> 00:33:17.940
So it was, really it was
basically unthinkable.

00:33:17.940 --> 00:33:21.180
I had grown-up with
it, it was impossible.

00:33:21.180 --> 00:33:26.640
The most disruptive event that
I can think of in my lifetime.

00:33:26.640 --> 00:33:29.650
But when I think back
over these last 30 years

00:33:29.650 --> 00:33:32.210
and what has happened
since it struck me

00:33:32.210 --> 00:33:36.890
that from this most
nonlinear event

00:33:36.890 --> 00:33:41.870
that you can imagine most
Germans have derived a

00:33:41.870 --> 00:33:45.830
thoroughly linear expectation
of what was to follow,

00:33:45.830 --> 00:33:49.640
and I don't think
there's another country

00:33:49.640 --> 00:33:53.320
where Francis Fukuyama's
thesis of the end of history

00:33:53.320 --> 00:33:58.370
after 1989 was as
popular as in Germany

00:33:58.370 --> 00:34:04.250
because it somehow fit
our own expectations

00:34:04.250 --> 00:34:06.270
and our hopes in many ways.

00:34:06.270 --> 00:34:11.980
You know, after having been on
the wrong side of history twice

00:34:11.980 --> 00:34:15.700
in the 20th Century the
country finally found itself

00:34:15.700 --> 00:34:20.240
on the right side of
history of stable democracy,

00:34:20.240 --> 00:34:23.410
a market economy, and to say

00:34:23.410 --> 00:34:26.190
that this is actually the
final destination of history

00:34:26.190 --> 00:34:28.330
and now everybody else
would have to change

00:34:28.330 --> 00:34:31.530
and essentially become like
us, but we had already arrived

00:34:31.530 --> 00:34:37.050
at the destination, was
very appealing as a thought.

00:34:37.050 --> 00:34:42.120
And so I think this assumption
of a grand convergence

00:34:42.120 --> 00:34:45.270
that would happen, first with
the transformation of central

00:34:45.270 --> 00:34:47.760
and eastern Europe,
then with a wave

00:34:47.760 --> 00:34:51.970
of democratization elsewhere,
but eventually everywhere,

00:34:51.970 --> 00:34:56.870
that was actually, that
was good and we would be

00:34:56.870 --> 00:35:00.430
at the center of it again.

00:35:00.430 --> 00:35:04.390
I think also that for a country
that had been burned so badly

00:35:04.390 --> 00:35:09.890
by sort of charismatic idea
of leadership the notion

00:35:09.890 --> 00:35:14.130
that personal agency didn't
really matter that much

00:35:14.130 --> 00:35:17.210
because it, you know leaders
would basically just administer

00:35:17.210 --> 00:35:20.840
the inevitable on a broader
flow of history that would lead

00:35:20.840 --> 00:35:24.180
in a predetermined
direction, also had something

00:35:24.180 --> 00:35:27.100
that was deeply appealing to
Germans much more so than,

00:35:27.100 --> 00:35:31.090
I don't know, French
or Americans or others.

00:35:31.090 --> 00:35:36.100
And, finally, what happened
since where I grew-up

00:35:36.100 --> 00:35:38.920
in West Germany, we were
sort of a frontline state

00:35:38.920 --> 00:35:42.700
in the cold war, highly
militarized, including lots

00:35:42.700 --> 00:35:45.600
of American troops,
nuclear weapons and the same

00:35:45.600 --> 00:35:48.690
on the other side
from the Soviets,

00:35:48.690 --> 00:35:55.630
with all of that disappearing
in the 1990s and the notion

00:35:55.630 --> 00:35:56.930
that for the first time

00:35:56.930 --> 00:36:00.400
in Germany's history the country
was surrounded only by friends,

00:36:00.400 --> 00:36:04.440
it basically drove threat
perception down to zero.

00:36:04.440 --> 00:36:09.030
If we wouldn't meddle in other
people's affairs nobody would

00:36:09.030 --> 00:36:10.370
meddle in ours,

00:36:10.370 --> 00:36:16.210
and so essentially what was
left was a trading state, right?

00:36:16.210 --> 00:36:19.660
So the limitations that had
been imposed in Germany one way

00:36:19.660 --> 00:36:24.140
or another after World War II
suddenly seemed to transform us

00:36:24.140 --> 00:36:30.070
into an avant-garde of history,
we were at the front of it

00:36:30.070 --> 00:36:32.800
and if we considered
the European Union

00:36:32.800 --> 00:36:34.100
to be the avant-garde

00:36:34.100 --> 00:36:36.690
of integration globally
Germany was seen

00:36:36.690 --> 00:36:39.160
as the avant-garde
within Europe.

00:36:39.160 --> 00:36:42.710
And I think, you know this is
sort of somewhat simplified

00:36:42.710 --> 00:36:44.620
and not everybody shared that,

00:36:44.620 --> 00:36:47.750
but I think it was a
pretty broad sentiment,

00:36:47.750 --> 00:36:52.370
including in the foreign policy,
security policy community.

00:36:52.370 --> 00:36:59.250
And it took us awhile because
in a way what this view

00:36:59.250 --> 00:37:04.290
of the international order
did, of which we were a product

00:37:04.290 --> 00:37:10.360
as the Federal Republic of
Germany created in 1949,

00:37:10.360 --> 00:37:16.220
what it did was it took our
own peculiar German history

00:37:16.220 --> 00:37:19.010
and allowed us to
universalize it.

00:37:19.010 --> 00:37:21.490
We took our own lessons
from history,

00:37:21.490 --> 00:37:26.250
never again the holocaust
and, therefore, a strong focus

00:37:26.250 --> 00:37:31.110
on human rights,
moving away from power,

00:37:31.110 --> 00:37:34.960
moving towards what you
could call a judicialization

00:37:34.960 --> 00:37:36.340
of international politics.

00:37:36.340 --> 00:37:39.830
So you move away from power
to sort of rule of law system,

00:37:39.830 --> 00:37:42.860
also in the international order,

00:37:42.860 --> 00:37:44.810
through international
institutions,

00:37:44.810 --> 00:37:47.360
through the creation of
an international court,

00:37:47.360 --> 00:37:50.940
international criminal
court in 1998

00:37:50.940 --> 00:37:57.250
that would have jurisdiction
not just for war crimes,

00:37:57.250 --> 00:37:58.810
but crimes against humanity,

00:37:58.810 --> 00:38:00.990
state aggression
and these things.

00:38:00.990 --> 00:38:05.430
But this was a path that
sort of perfectly conformed

00:38:05.430 --> 00:38:09.230
to our preferences, but also
to our historical lessons.

00:38:09.230 --> 00:38:12.580
And so we could universalize
the rather difficult,

00:38:12.580 --> 00:38:14.370
peculiar German history.

00:38:14.370 --> 00:38:20.410
And this feeling, this
sense of being in sync

00:38:20.410 --> 00:38:27.070
with history started to
crumble I think really in 2014,

00:38:27.070 --> 00:38:29.550
and there was, if you go back
now you can see the signs

00:38:29.550 --> 00:38:33.520
on the wall earlier, of
course, but the real,

00:38:33.520 --> 00:38:37.720
the actual that it hit
home I think the invasion

00:38:37.720 --> 00:38:41.670
and annexation of Crimea
and the Russian aggression

00:38:41.670 --> 00:38:44.910
in Eastern Ukraine and
the Donbas was the sign

00:38:44.910 --> 00:38:49.300
that the happy days
of post-wall Europe

00:38:49.300 --> 00:38:52.010
and international
order were really over.

00:38:52.010 --> 00:38:56.330
And then suddenly once you
realized that you also realized

00:38:56.330 --> 00:38:59.480
that Russia had already
years before begun

00:38:59.480 --> 00:39:02.460
to define its own future,
actually more in opposition

00:39:02.460 --> 00:39:05.070
to the West, and no
longer in cooperation

00:39:05.070 --> 00:39:07.410
or on a path of convergence.

00:39:07.410 --> 00:39:09.750
And at the same it was
actually also true for China

00:39:09.750 --> 00:39:12.280
under the new President
Xi Jinping

00:39:12.280 --> 00:39:17.730
who would still modernize, still
grow, but not open, rather close

00:39:17.730 --> 00:39:19.510
and become more repressive.

00:39:19.510 --> 00:39:25.400
And there's sort of a far
more competitive element

00:39:25.400 --> 00:39:30.060
in the international system
than we'd like to believe.

00:39:30.060 --> 00:39:36.180
But these were still all
outside pressures and datapoints

00:39:36.180 --> 00:39:39.930
that signaled the problem.

00:39:39.930 --> 00:39:45.040
I think 2016, first
with the BREXIT and then

00:39:45.040 --> 00:39:47.500
with the election
of the US President,

00:39:47.500 --> 00:39:50.690
represented a different
dimension.

00:39:50.690 --> 00:39:58.110
I mean the BREXIT decision ran
directly counter to the notion

00:39:58.110 --> 00:40:01.280
that the process of integration
in Europe had something

00:40:01.280 --> 00:40:05.120
that was irreversible,
that was sort of necessary,

00:40:05.120 --> 00:40:08.080
that it conformed to
a historical pattern

00:40:08.080 --> 00:40:11.290
of ever deeper integration.

00:40:11.290 --> 00:40:16.140
And the British said, oh, we
can actually turn-off and go off

00:40:16.140 --> 00:40:20.850
in the opposite direction, which
is a serious blow for Europe

00:40:20.850 --> 00:40:24.200
but also a serious blow to
the way we Germans looked

00:40:24.200 --> 00:40:26.280
at Europe and Europe's future.

00:40:26.280 --> 00:40:30.250
And with the election of an
American President who would go

00:40:30.250 --> 00:40:35.160
out in public, he and his top
advisors, and say there is no

00:40:35.160 --> 00:40:39.560
such thing as an international
community, everybody is

00:40:39.560 --> 00:40:44.270
out there for him or herself,
to look after him or herself,

00:40:44.270 --> 00:40:46.310
that ran directly counter

00:40:46.310 --> 00:40:51.310
to the second grand German
lesson of never alone.

00:40:51.310 --> 00:40:54.490
So, as Ivan said, there are
other countries who can go back

00:40:54.490 --> 00:40:58.780
to a more national
conception of their own country

00:40:58.780 --> 00:41:00.500
in the international system.

00:41:00.500 --> 00:41:05.410
You know, the French have their
goalist tradition of France

00:41:05.410 --> 00:41:09.480
and the world that looks
after itself, but for Germany

00:41:09.480 --> 00:41:11.190
that doesn't really
exist anymore

00:41:11.190 --> 00:41:14.290
because all these more national
conceptions have all been

00:41:14.290 --> 00:41:18.360
contaminated in the Nazi years
and they now basically belong

00:41:18.360 --> 00:41:21.610
to the political fringes in
Germany's political system

00:41:21.610 --> 00:41:26.970
for all the mainstream parties,
all those centrous parties.

00:41:26.970 --> 00:41:32.260
There is nothing but a
multilateralist foreign policy

00:41:32.260 --> 00:41:38.290
that looks at Germany's future
always linked to its neighbors,

00:41:38.290 --> 00:41:44.530
but limited but also
legitimized in organizations

00:41:44.530 --> 00:41:46.720
that include partners.

00:41:46.720 --> 00:41:51.230
And that is why I would say
there's no other country

00:41:51.230 --> 00:41:56.840
that I could think of that is
as challenged by the world view

00:41:56.840 --> 00:42:00.240
as it is articulated by
the current US President

00:42:00.240 --> 00:42:04.790
as is Germany, that in itself
looks at itself so much

00:42:04.790 --> 00:42:07.930
as an American post-war
creation.

00:42:07.930 --> 00:42:15.350
And this conceptual challenge
now to imagine the world

00:42:15.350 --> 00:42:19.200
and our role in the world at
a moment when our own lessons

00:42:19.200 --> 00:42:22.650
of history and the course

00:42:22.650 --> 00:42:25.630
of the international political
system sort of diverge

00:42:25.630 --> 00:42:27.620
after we thought they
would be, they would run

00:42:27.620 --> 00:42:32.030
in parallel forever hopefully,
but certainly for longer

00:42:32.030 --> 00:42:35.980
than it did is a pretty
painful situation in Germany

00:42:35.980 --> 00:42:38.910
and it's just starting a
foreign policy debate of, well,

00:42:38.910 --> 00:42:41.450
what is then Germany's
role and what should it do?

00:42:41.450 --> 00:42:44.810
And most of that
points to Europe,

00:42:44.810 --> 00:42:49.380
invest in the European
Union, invest in a network

00:42:49.380 --> 00:42:53.080
of multilaterally
oriented nations,

00:42:53.080 --> 00:42:57.970
and that is where
Ivan's point comes in.

00:42:57.970 --> 00:43:03.100
You can sort of a national
political system can survive a

00:43:03.100 --> 00:43:05.120
populist challenge,

00:43:05.120 --> 00:43:09.690
maybe sometimes a populist
government can even help to sort

00:43:09.690 --> 00:43:14.490
of correct or redefine the
national political landscape,

00:43:14.490 --> 00:43:21.570
the issues that are important,
and then sort of it moves on.

00:43:21.570 --> 00:43:26.530
It is quite difficult to imagine
the same for the European Union

00:43:26.530 --> 00:43:32.570
because if you think of
it it is made up of 28

00:43:32.570 --> 00:43:37.130
and once the British have
left 27 member states,

00:43:37.130 --> 00:43:41.750
and it's working around
a table in Brussels

00:43:41.750 --> 00:43:45.810
where all these countries
larger and smaller come together

00:43:45.810 --> 00:43:49.850
and basically hammer out a
compromise that is, of course,

00:43:49.850 --> 00:43:58.040
always imperfect but that
is based on the assumption

00:43:58.040 --> 00:44:03.800
that in the longer term and if
you define national interests

00:44:03.800 --> 00:44:10.140
in a wider perspective it is
beneficial to all of them.

00:44:10.140 --> 00:44:15.050
And if you narrow your
definition of national interest

00:44:15.050 --> 00:44:20.130
and you shorten the time
horizon then what you do is you

00:44:20.130 --> 00:44:25.390
basically close the space, the
space shrinks for compromise

00:44:25.390 --> 00:44:29.490
around the Brussels table
until it disappears entirely.

00:44:29.490 --> 00:44:33.490
Everyone is only looking
after his or her own interests

00:44:33.490 --> 00:44:37.510
on this very day, on this very
issue that is on the table

00:44:37.510 --> 00:44:40.110
and not considering that
you may need the partners

00:44:40.110 --> 00:44:45.200
and their enlightened
self-interests the next day,

00:44:45.200 --> 00:44:49.590
then there is no room for
compromise or it shrinks

00:44:49.590 --> 00:44:52.760
to a degree where it makes the
European Union actually look

00:44:52.760 --> 00:44:54.140
like a body that is not able

00:44:54.140 --> 00:44:57.860
to produce any meaningful
solution for any real problem.

00:44:57.860 --> 00:45:02.600
So I think for me this
is it's really a question

00:45:02.600 --> 00:45:04.710
of how you define
national interests,

00:45:04.710 --> 00:45:08.930
there's a great expression
in Tocqueville's Democracy

00:45:08.930 --> 00:45:14.880
in America where he talks of the
self-interest rightly understood

00:45:14.880 --> 00:45:16.810
and I think you can
define self-interest

00:45:16.810 --> 00:45:18.110
in very different ways.

00:45:18.110 --> 00:45:22.950
And the Germans have learned
this lesson in a hard way

00:45:22.950 --> 00:45:28.340
that we're better off today
and in this integrated Europe

00:45:28.340 --> 00:45:33.490
than at any point in our history
before and it has something

00:45:33.490 --> 00:45:37.160
to do with trying to define
our won self-interests in a way

00:45:37.160 --> 00:45:39.440
that actually includes
the interests of neighbors

00:45:39.440 --> 00:45:41.620
and partners and
others on the continent

00:45:41.620 --> 00:45:43.990
and in taking a longer view.

00:45:43.990 --> 00:45:48.490
And what puzzles us now
is that not just here

00:45:48.490 --> 00:45:51.070
in the United States,
but also elsewhere

00:45:51.070 --> 00:45:54.470
in the world national
interest is defined

00:45:54.470 --> 00:45:58.120
in an increasingly narrow
and short-term perspective

00:45:58.120 --> 00:46:00.490
and that leaves us
in a situation

00:46:00.490 --> 00:46:06.630
where the solution we thought we
had found to the German problem

00:46:06.630 --> 00:46:09.120
of being the biggest
country in the center

00:46:09.120 --> 00:46:13.630
of the European Continent too
big to be just one among many,

00:46:13.630 --> 00:46:19.080
but not big enough and strong
enough to rule all others,

00:46:19.080 --> 00:46:23.160
that solution may not be as
permanent as we had hoped.

00:46:23.160 --> 00:46:24.580
&gt;&gt; Ivan Krastev:
Thank you very much.

00:46:24.580 --> 00:46:26.610
I do believe we are going
to have time to discuss it,

00:46:26.610 --> 00:46:30.290
because some of the more
radical Euro skeptics are going

00:46:30.290 --> 00:46:32.390
to ask questions like this.

00:46:32.390 --> 00:46:36.880
Yugoslavia did not manage to
survive the end of the cold war

00:46:36.880 --> 00:46:40.310
because the very existence of
the state was very much embedded

00:46:40.310 --> 00:46:43.110
in a certain type of
international context,

00:46:43.110 --> 00:46:46.390
could European Union
become the major victim,

00:46:46.390 --> 00:46:48.250
is it through disintegration
of the EU,

00:46:48.250 --> 00:46:52.460
of the end of a liberal order
as an international environment?

00:46:52.460 --> 00:46:55.460
And I do believe this is a
fair question and this is why

00:46:55.460 --> 00:46:58.750
for us basically what
Europeans are asking about this,

00:46:58.750 --> 00:47:03.940
this is in a way we're much
more nervous than many others.

00:47:03.940 --> 00:47:06.220
But the interesting story
about liberal order was

00:47:06.220 --> 00:47:08.530
that it was always about the
relations between states,

00:47:08.530 --> 00:47:11.240
but also what is
happening within the states.

00:47:11.240 --> 00:47:13.000
And when people have
been very positive

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:15.510
on the liberal order
starting with the beginning

00:47:15.510 --> 00:47:20.540
of the 21st Century one of the
critical countries was Turkey.

00:47:20.540 --> 00:47:23.390
Opening of Turkey was
critical for something

00:47:23.390 --> 00:47:26.640
that is happening
simply between states,

00:47:26.640 --> 00:47:27.940
but how the new relations

00:47:27.940 --> 00:47:31.110
between states is starting
basically to change things.

00:47:31.110 --> 00:47:34.610
And we're going to
have basically the view

00:47:34.610 --> 00:47:38.500
of what is happening,
the Turkish perspective

00:47:38.500 --> 00:47:41.860
of these relations between the
foreign and domestic politics

00:47:41.860 --> 00:47:44.580
and talking about one
of the key countries

00:47:44.580 --> 00:47:46.910
that in a way also
symbolizes something

00:47:46.910 --> 00:47:50.100
that can become problematic with
the crisis of the liberal order.

00:47:50.100 --> 00:47:54.820
And Solly Roselle [assumed
spelling] is the person

00:47:54.820 --> 00:47:56.120
to say this.

00:47:56.120 --> 00:47:59.070
&gt;&gt; Solly Roselle: Well,
I prepared other notes,

00:47:59.070 --> 00:48:01.770
but if you want me to talk
about those I'll talk.

00:48:01.770 --> 00:48:03.110
&gt;&gt; Ivan Krastev: This is
the problem with Turkey,

00:48:03.110 --> 00:48:08.980
also as indicated, they
always prepare other notes.

00:48:08.980 --> 00:48:10.280
&gt;&gt; Solly Roselle: Yes, okay.

00:48:10.280 --> 00:48:15.340
I mean Turkey's behavior
today cannot be dissociated

00:48:15.340 --> 00:48:19.020
with what has gone
in the past 30 years.

00:48:19.020 --> 00:48:22.980
It's interesting, in eight
months' time it will be 30th

00:48:22.980 --> 00:48:28.840
anniversary of Francis
Fukuyama's article published

00:48:28.840 --> 00:48:31.390
in national interest.

00:48:31.390 --> 00:48:36.220
And although Fukuyama wrote
a lot more and recently kind

00:48:36.220 --> 00:48:39.980
of distanced himself from 30
years ago I guess he will always

00:48:39.980 --> 00:48:46.300
be remembered or damned because
of the end of history article,

00:48:46.300 --> 00:48:51.270
which of course ended like his
doctoral dissertation advisor

00:48:51.270 --> 00:48:55.850
Huntington's article
with a question mark.

00:48:55.850 --> 00:48:58.710
And that question mark
of course we dismiss.

00:48:58.710 --> 00:49:04.230
And in a way for both of those
articles, that is end of history

00:49:04.230 --> 00:49:09.610
and the clash of civilizations,
Turkey was a critical country

00:49:09.610 --> 00:49:13.770
because it actually was
always and partially

00:49:13.770 --> 00:49:15.070
because of the geography

00:49:15.070 --> 00:49:20.430
on which it sat a
Janus-faced country.

00:49:20.430 --> 00:49:24.100
And in a way Turkey also
showed a lot of adaptability

00:49:24.100 --> 00:49:29.840
to the requirements of the new
order that was emerging in 1989,

00:49:29.840 --> 00:49:37.280
wasted the 1990s, and then
almost reinvented itself.

00:49:37.280 --> 00:49:44.870
And I have to say that the
Clinton Administration was,

00:49:44.870 --> 00:49:49.880
mainly thanks to the
late Richard Holbrook,

00:49:49.880 --> 00:49:56.530
understood Turkey's role and
actually pushed the country,

00:49:56.530 --> 00:50:01.010
pushed the European Union and
pushed American foreign policy

00:50:01.010 --> 00:50:06.660
to encourage Turkey to actually
play that, not the bridge role,

00:50:06.660 --> 00:50:10.730
bridge in my judgment is
really the wrong metaphor

00:50:10.730 --> 00:50:13.450
because bridges don't
belong anywhere,

00:50:13.450 --> 00:50:16.060
but Turkey as a mediator,

00:50:16.060 --> 00:50:19.370
a country that could
actually speak the language

00:50:19.370 --> 00:50:22.260
of the three regions
that surround it.

00:50:22.260 --> 00:50:27.160
And what I call Turkey
surrounded or at the center

00:50:27.160 --> 00:50:32.930
of what I call three
geopolitical ecosystems,

00:50:32.930 --> 00:50:37.110
the European one, Russia,
central Asia caucus is one,

00:50:37.110 --> 00:50:39.000
and of course the Middle East.

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:42.460
Ecosystem in the Middle East
may not be fitting these days,

00:50:42.460 --> 00:50:43.800
but still.

00:50:43.800 --> 00:50:49.130
And Turkey, to the extent
that Turkey could rise

00:50:49.130 --> 00:50:53.440
to the occasion and
manage to actually mediate

00:50:53.440 --> 00:50:56.680
between those three, then it
would have accomplished its role

00:50:56.680 --> 00:50:59.040
and that is precisely almost

00:50:59.040 --> 00:51:02.570
in so many words how
Richard Holbrook defined it

00:51:02.570 --> 00:51:06.900
and the Clinton Administration
tried to push us

00:51:06.900 --> 00:51:09.210
and the Europeans
in that direction.

00:51:09.210 --> 00:51:15.240
In fact, in an article he wrote
in 1994 for Foreign Affairs,

00:51:15.240 --> 00:51:20.030
which he had a strange kind
of because Holbrook wrote,

00:51:20.030 --> 00:51:24.850
during the cold war Germany
was the frontline state,

00:51:24.850 --> 00:51:28.740
in the post cold war period
Turkey is the frontline state,

00:51:28.740 --> 00:51:31.500
when there was no war
or the threat of war,

00:51:31.500 --> 00:51:34.470
so what was the front, what
did the war consist of?

00:51:34.470 --> 00:51:38.740
And that was, of course, to
avoid what Huntington raised,

00:51:38.740 --> 00:51:40.430
clashal civilizations.

00:51:40.430 --> 00:51:43.820
Maybe this was formulated
wrongly,

00:51:43.820 --> 00:51:47.220
I mean in retrospect I would
think it was, but no doubt

00:51:47.220 --> 00:51:50.820
that issue of identity
starting with the dissolution

00:51:50.820 --> 00:51:54.600
of the Yugoslavia, the
Yuan Dong massacres,

00:51:54.600 --> 00:51:59.620
and all that had actually been
with us and actually hunting us

00:51:59.620 --> 00:52:02.820
and we are now dissociating
ourselves from it

00:52:02.820 --> 00:52:05.060
because interest has come back.

00:52:05.060 --> 00:52:09.010
I wish to take a detour
before I go back to Turkey

00:52:09.010 --> 00:52:12.740
and to talk a bit about
the United States,

00:52:12.740 --> 00:52:17.490
since our topic is
hypocrisy in our project.

00:52:17.490 --> 00:52:21.850
I have a very hard
time personally

00:52:21.850 --> 00:52:30.050
to accept the bemoaning
of many liberals today

00:52:30.050 --> 00:52:35.020
that the Trump Administration's
policies are ending the liberal

00:52:35.020 --> 00:52:36.320
world order.

00:52:36.320 --> 00:52:38.240
First of all, five
years ago we didn't talk

00:52:38.240 --> 00:52:40.440
about the liberal world order.

00:52:40.440 --> 00:52:43.600
And, secondly and
much more importantly,

00:52:43.600 --> 00:52:46.240
who broke that order?

00:52:46.240 --> 00:52:49.480
Many of the people today
who lament the passing

00:52:49.480 --> 00:52:55.050
of the liberal world order were
cheerleaders for the Iraq war,

00:52:55.050 --> 00:52:58.940
whether they came from the right
or they came from the left.

00:52:58.940 --> 00:53:04.650
They were the intellectual
promoters of an act

00:53:04.650 --> 00:53:08.490
by the most powerful country
in the world at the time

00:53:08.490 --> 00:53:14.800
to break the rules that
actually itself formulated

00:53:14.800 --> 00:53:18.970
at the beginning of
the cold war era.

00:53:18.970 --> 00:53:24.810
We really cannot have an
intelligent or a fair discussion

00:53:24.810 --> 00:53:29.660
about Russia and what it does,
about China and what it does,

00:53:29.660 --> 00:53:35.400
about Turkey and what it does,
we doubt accepting the fact

00:53:35.400 --> 00:53:41.140
that the rules in a major
way were first broken

00:53:41.140 --> 00:53:45.620
by that country which
actually set them.

00:53:45.620 --> 00:53:49.460
And it will be very
difficult in my judgment

00:53:49.460 --> 00:53:51.410
under those circumstances

00:53:51.410 --> 00:53:55.700
to put Humpty Dumpty
back together, okay?

00:53:56.970 --> 00:54:03.230
Secondly, we also have
to acknowledge in my view

00:54:03.230 --> 00:54:10.360
and I hear what Thomas has
said literally and then

00:54:10.360 --> 00:54:15.150
but I also add to it there
was a sense of complacency

00:54:15.150 --> 00:54:18.680
and that's what the end of
history debate was all about.

00:54:18.680 --> 00:54:23.660
We've reached the search,
the end of the search,

00:54:23.660 --> 00:54:27.800
there will be nothing
better which blinded those

00:54:27.800 --> 00:54:33.180
who actually benefited
from the unilateral moment,

00:54:33.180 --> 00:54:36.650
it blinded them to
the inequities

00:54:36.650 --> 00:54:41.350
that the economic system
generated, it blinded them

00:54:41.350 --> 00:54:43.950
to the dialectic
of globalization

00:54:43.950 --> 00:54:45.880
that everybody championed.

00:54:45.880 --> 00:54:50.800
That is you could not
have a win-win result

00:54:50.800 --> 00:54:59.280
from globalization forever,
and it turned out that those

00:54:59.280 --> 00:55:02.810
who support for the liberal
order and it was necessary,

00:55:02.810 --> 00:55:09.020
that is the working people
of developed countries ended

00:55:09.020 --> 00:55:13.380
up on the losing side of that
development and in return,

00:55:13.380 --> 00:55:16.800
of course, millions,
hundreds of millions of people

00:55:16.800 --> 00:55:21.480
in the developing world
actually benefitted immensely,

00:55:21.480 --> 00:55:24.630
but those who ruled those,

00:55:24.630 --> 00:55:29.420
I mean the developed countries
did not take into account

00:55:29.420 --> 00:55:34.180
that the legitimacy of what
they were pursuing depended

00:55:34.180 --> 00:55:38.630
on taking care of those who
were actually being left behind.

00:55:38.630 --> 00:55:44.370
And I'm not certain that that
blindness has been cured,

00:55:44.370 --> 00:55:49.550
even now, because without
understanding this we really

00:55:49.550 --> 00:55:54.930
cannot understand or begin
to treat the populist rage,

00:55:54.930 --> 00:55:59.060
whether it is of a leftist
kind or a rightest kind.

00:55:59.060 --> 00:56:04.840
Secondly, not to be reductionist
in terms of inequities,

00:56:04.840 --> 00:56:09.230
I mean economic inequalities,
obviously the top

00:56:09.230 --> 00:56:14.860
of a liberal order also
reflected a certain

00:56:14.860 --> 00:56:18.980
understanding of what the
culture of that order was

00:56:18.980 --> 00:56:23.250
and I guess one does get carried
away with one's own rhetoric

00:56:23.250 --> 00:56:26.970
and beliefs and you
start belittling those

00:56:26.970 --> 00:56:30.720
who do not necessarily
fit your own description

00:56:30.720 --> 00:56:34.990
of what the ideal life or ideal
identity ought to be like.

00:56:34.990 --> 00:56:40.240
And now once the vase is broken
these are really very difficult

00:56:40.240 --> 00:56:43.230
things to fix.

00:56:43.230 --> 00:56:47.970
I mean Germany's
unemployment rate is what, 3.8,

00:56:47.970 --> 00:56:51.730
Austria's is probably
below zero, I don't know.

00:56:51.730 --> 00:56:55.570
The United States today
is at 3.7 and all that.

00:56:55.570 --> 00:57:00.620
And if it was even more
equitably done once those

00:57:00.620 --> 00:57:04.490
questions have been put on
stage it's very difficult

00:57:04.490 --> 00:57:08.850
to actually change the
conversation back to one

00:57:08.850 --> 00:57:11.390
where you use the terms
that you used to be using.

00:57:11.390 --> 00:57:14.370
So we've got to accept that.

00:57:14.370 --> 00:57:19.670
And coming to Rosa's question,
do we go back to what we used

00:57:19.670 --> 00:57:22.130
to have once the blip is over?

00:57:22.130 --> 00:57:25.070
The blip may not be over,
that's one thing and, second,

00:57:25.070 --> 00:57:29.210
even if it is over we cannot
go back, I mean we're back

00:57:29.210 --> 00:57:34.030
to Ancient Greece, right, you
cannot take, we don't get baited

00:57:34.030 --> 00:57:36.600
in the same way but twice, okay?

00:57:36.600 --> 00:57:43.050
And the Greeks have a lot of
wisdom to give us on that.

00:57:43.050 --> 00:57:45.200
So coming to Turkey, Turkey

00:57:45.200 --> 00:57:50.920
of course is a very flexible
country or it can be.

00:57:50.920 --> 00:57:56.420
Okay, we will play the
dialogue of civilization scarred

00:57:56.420 --> 00:57:59.510
and we will give the
European Union a chance

00:57:59.510 --> 00:58:02.790
as the European Union was
going to give us a chance,

00:58:02.790 --> 00:58:07.270
and I must say for a very,
in retrospect of course,

00:58:07.270 --> 00:58:14.260
for a fleeting moment both sides
actually dropped the hypocrisy,

00:58:14.260 --> 00:58:19.470
double talk and insincerity that
defined their relations forever.

00:58:19.470 --> 00:58:21.070
Very fleeting moment.

00:58:21.070 --> 00:58:26.150
I wish that both those who were
in positions of responsibility

00:58:26.150 --> 00:58:28.290
in the European Union and those

00:58:28.290 --> 00:58:32.380
in Turkey actually truly
understood the meaning

00:58:32.380 --> 00:58:36.540
and the potency of that moment
and actually went ahead with it.

00:58:36.540 --> 00:58:41.950
That wasn't to be, we're now
back to our usual positions.

00:58:41.950 --> 00:58:45.570
But in between, though,
because of the weakening

00:58:45.570 --> 00:58:50.380
of the international system,
and I personally do not talk

00:58:50.380 --> 00:58:53.240
in terms of the return
of geopolitics,

00:58:53.240 --> 00:58:57.800
I'm more comfortable with
geopolitics finally waking

00:58:57.800 --> 00:59:00.880
up from a long sleep because
I don't think geopolitics

00:59:00.880 --> 00:59:02.180
ever died.

00:59:02.180 --> 00:59:04.960
The United States exercised it.

00:59:04.960 --> 00:59:08.090
With the return of geopolitics,
declining American power

00:59:08.090 --> 00:59:13.730
and the colossal failures of
the Iraq war Turkey, of course,

00:59:13.730 --> 00:59:18.010
repossessed for itself
an identity

00:59:18.010 --> 00:59:20.140
that it is usually
very comfortable with,

00:59:20.140 --> 00:59:24.570
and that is a post-imperial
power which wishes

00:59:24.570 --> 00:59:30.360
to become an important not
to be ignored regional power.

00:59:30.360 --> 00:59:33.080
And I must say I also detect

00:59:33.080 --> 00:59:40.950
in Turkey a post-imperial
trauma syndrome.

00:59:40.950 --> 00:59:44.360
I guess Mr. Cooper could
understand me well,

00:59:44.360 --> 00:59:46.310
they lost an empire as well.

00:59:46.310 --> 00:59:49.560
The thing is our trauma
really came a bit late,

00:59:49.560 --> 00:59:53.110
about nine years later, and
now we're trying to make-up

00:59:53.110 --> 00:59:56.780
for lost time and,
therefore, all of the regions

00:59:56.780 --> 01:00:01.360
that surround us are for
Turkey fair playing in terms

01:00:01.360 --> 01:00:09.470
of projecting Turkey's
power and vision

01:00:09.470 --> 01:00:14.010
of I guess hegemonic domination.

01:00:14.010 --> 01:00:18.350
And whether or not Turkey will
be able to do that still is

01:00:18.350 --> 01:00:22.330
out in the open, but
I'll start, I'll conclude

01:00:22.330 --> 01:00:26.010
with what I'm sure
most of you at least

01:00:26.010 --> 01:00:29.560
with some interest are
following, what happened

01:00:29.560 --> 01:00:33.230
to Mr. Khashoggi and what kind

01:00:33.230 --> 01:00:37.580
of policy Turkey is
pursuing in that?

01:00:37.580 --> 01:00:42.680
I have to say the
Khashoggi affair fits right

01:00:42.680 --> 01:00:45.580
into our project.

01:00:47.140 --> 01:00:51.210
There was a murder, a
rather gruesome one.

01:00:51.210 --> 01:00:54.600
It is now I guess pretty obvious

01:00:54.600 --> 01:00:57.680
that the Turkish
Government was aware of it,

01:00:57.680 --> 01:01:04.100
the British Government
knew about it in advance,

01:01:04.100 --> 01:01:06.590
and unless the American
intelligence was

01:01:06.590 --> 01:01:10.780
as usual sleeping on the job
they must also have had some

01:01:10.780 --> 01:01:14.350
inclination as to what
was going to happen.

01:01:14.350 --> 01:01:18.170
And, therefore, we are now
playing a game and the game,

01:01:18.170 --> 01:01:21.810
therefore, beyond
the moral aspects

01:01:21.810 --> 01:01:28.080
of the murder this
has now become a dance

01:01:28.080 --> 01:01:31.060
between three partners.

01:01:31.060 --> 01:01:35.810
How will Turkey treat
Saudi Arabia?

01:01:35.810 --> 01:01:40.560
How will Turkey or will
the United States side

01:01:40.560 --> 01:01:45.510
with the Turkish
narrative and then dump MBS,

01:01:45.510 --> 01:01:50.220
or as the President said
initially I have arms to sell,

01:01:50.220 --> 01:01:52.550
I really cannot jeopardize that?

01:01:52.550 --> 01:01:53.850
That remains to be seen.

01:01:53.850 --> 01:01:57.350
I mean again he was not
hypocritical, but it's obvious

01:01:57.350 --> 01:01:59.840
that for this particular
issue at least

01:01:59.840 --> 01:02:04.420
for the moment the American
political system for a variety

01:02:04.420 --> 01:02:06.850
of reasons and American media

01:02:06.850 --> 01:02:11.520
and maybe civil society are
not going to let this go.

01:02:11.520 --> 01:02:17.370
And if, indeed, this leads to
a dumping of MBS as a result

01:02:17.370 --> 01:02:19.920
that will really be a victory

01:02:19.920 --> 01:02:27.520
for a noncynical approach
to power relations.

01:02:27.520 --> 01:02:31.830
And if with all the
problems that it had

01:02:31.830 --> 01:02:36.080
so far Turkey I think
managed it relatively well,

01:02:36.080 --> 01:02:40.800
protecting national interests
but also keeping interest alive

01:02:40.800 --> 01:02:45.120
and also giving enough
information.

01:02:45.120 --> 01:02:51.340
And at the end of the day this
may turn out to be the defining

01:02:51.340 --> 01:02:56.200
or a decisive moment
for the Middle East

01:02:56.200 --> 01:02:59.120
to see whether it will
