01:16:08.560 --> 01:16:12.170
based on watching the house
of cards this also can turn

01:16:12.170 --> 01:16:16.510
to be not the greatest
idea, but I'll go to Solly.

01:16:16.510 --> 01:16:20.080
&gt;&gt; Solly Roselle: You want
to find out Turkey's policy

01:16:20.080 --> 01:16:27.600
in Syria and its
closeness to Russia, well,

01:16:27.600 --> 01:16:30.980
Turkey made a number
of miscalculations

01:16:30.980 --> 01:16:35.190
and I think it's a tribute
to its geopolitical position

01:16:35.190 --> 01:16:40.780
that despite those errors it is
still as they call at the table.

01:16:40.780 --> 01:16:45.810
The major error Turkey
committed, apart from thinking

01:16:45.810 --> 01:16:48.420
that Assad would go easily,

01:16:48.420 --> 01:16:57.710
was to attack a Russian plane
thinking that this might lead

01:16:57.710 --> 01:17:00.920
to a mobilization of
NATO on its side in order

01:17:00.920 --> 01:17:04.390
to actually pursue
its policies in Syria.

01:17:04.390 --> 01:17:08.470
It didn't work, in fact,
in return the Russians kind

01:17:08.470 --> 01:17:17.290
of punished Turkey, and in the
meantime the United States,

01:17:17.290 --> 01:17:21.510
Turkey's ally, has
gotten even more intimate

01:17:21.510 --> 01:17:25.570
with Turkey's sworn enemies,

01:17:25.570 --> 01:17:30.140
that is the PKK's
Syrian branch, PYD.

01:17:30.140 --> 01:17:35.200
That led Turkey to reconsider
its relations with Russia

01:17:35.200 --> 01:17:38.550
and it also led the Russians
to reconsider their relations

01:17:38.550 --> 01:17:42.430
with Turkey, which actually
was becoming a bit desperate.

01:17:42.430 --> 01:17:46.980
And they allowed Turkey
to do a number of things

01:17:46.980 --> 01:17:51.440
that Turkey could not without
Russian permission could do

01:17:51.440 --> 01:17:52.740
in Syria.

01:17:52.740 --> 01:17:58.500
So for the moment Turkey is
using America's indecisiveness

01:17:58.500 --> 01:18:04.230
and kind of weakness and
the Russian's immense desire

01:18:04.230 --> 01:18:09.080
to divorce Turkey from
NATO, playing both sides.

01:18:09.080 --> 01:18:11.900
How long that can go on
I really do not know,

01:18:11.900 --> 01:18:17.390
but so far Turkey was able
I think with both a blink

01:18:17.390 --> 01:18:20.460
from the United States and
with the help of the Russians

01:18:20.460 --> 01:18:24.390
to make sure that the
PYD could not control all

01:18:24.390 --> 01:18:26.380
of its southern border.

01:18:26.380 --> 01:18:30.840
And that to a certain
extent resolves Turkey's

01:18:30.840 --> 01:18:32.600
security problem.

01:18:32.600 --> 01:18:39.140
And from this point onwards
what will happen between Turkey

01:18:39.140 --> 01:18:40.880
and Russia and between Turkey

01:18:40.880 --> 01:18:44.530
and the United States will
be determined in my judgment

01:18:44.530 --> 01:18:47.760
by also what happens between
Russia and the United States

01:18:47.760 --> 01:18:51.840
for the conclusion of
the Syrian debacle.

01:18:51.840 --> 01:18:57.980
My sense is that peace is
not to come very soon and if

01:18:57.980 --> 01:18:59.990
that is the case
Turkey will continue

01:18:59.990 --> 01:19:02.520
to be administering the areas

01:19:02.520 --> 01:19:07.110
that its military operations
actually made it possible

01:19:07.110 --> 01:19:10.840
for it to occupy.

01:19:10.840 --> 01:19:12.140
&gt;&gt; Ivan Krastev: Thomas?

01:19:12.140 --> 01:19:13.480
&gt;&gt; Thomas Bagger: Yes, I'll
try to make two points.

01:19:13.480 --> 01:19:16.320
The first one to
the laziness charge

01:19:16.320 --> 01:19:19.070
and the languages question.

01:19:20.380 --> 01:19:23.180
I think this sort of laziness,

01:19:23.180 --> 01:19:25.740
it relates a bit
to what Ivan said.

01:19:25.740 --> 01:19:30.740
We were very good with grand
generalizations and again

01:19:30.740 --> 01:19:33.340
to the argument I tried to
make earlier, if you believe

01:19:33.340 --> 01:19:35.960
that everyone else becomes
like you you don't have

01:19:35.960 --> 01:19:39.330
to study their peculiar
circumstances, right?

01:19:39.330 --> 01:19:42.030
Why they think what they
think, how they got there,

01:19:42.030 --> 01:19:46.750
and how they will, how they
look at their own future.

01:19:46.750 --> 01:19:52.240
So just one example in the
cold war understanding Moscow

01:19:52.240 --> 01:19:54.870
and the Kremlin was
existential for Germany

01:19:54.870 --> 01:19:57.870
and there was quite a bit of
intellectual and academic effort

01:19:57.870 --> 01:19:59.300
and resources put into that.

01:19:59.300 --> 01:20:03.320
After 1989 we dissolved
most of these institutions,

01:20:03.320 --> 01:20:04.620
it was no longer interesting.

01:20:04.620 --> 01:20:06.870
They would modernize and
eventually, you know,

01:20:06.870 --> 01:20:11.450
they would become like us and
we could speak English with them

01:20:11.450 --> 01:20:14.870
about how long it would
take them to get there.

01:20:14.870 --> 01:20:19.390
Now two years ago we
recreated an Institute

01:20:19.390 --> 01:20:22.490
for Eastern European and
International Studies

01:20:22.490 --> 01:20:27.590
because we realized this
is not going to happen.

01:20:27.590 --> 01:20:30.660
There was a laziness certainly
in the assumption that we had

01:20:30.660 --> 01:20:35.610
or in our expectation, and we
need to understand the debates,

01:20:35.610 --> 01:20:40.290
the intellectual concepts in
places, not just like Russia

01:20:40.290 --> 01:20:44.630
but also in central Asia, in
eastern Europe sort of east

01:20:44.630 --> 01:20:46.550
of the European Union.

01:20:46.550 --> 01:20:51.120
So in that sense I
would go along with you.

01:20:51.120 --> 01:20:54.120
In a different way I don't think
the charge is entirely fair

01:20:54.120 --> 01:20:56.960
because it is also true

01:20:56.960 --> 01:21:01.580
that international relations
today compared to the days

01:21:01.580 --> 01:21:03.870
when they conceptualized the
Brattenwood's [assumed spelling]

01:21:03.870 --> 01:21:09.450
institutions is infinitely
more complex, more states,

01:21:09.450 --> 01:21:13.040
more interdependence, more
interaction, more stakeholders,

01:21:13.040 --> 01:21:15.290
not states only but
others as well.

01:21:15.290 --> 01:21:18.630
Just take the climate
negotiations as one example.

01:21:18.630 --> 01:21:25.590
So there's an infinite necessity
to invest time and energy

01:21:25.590 --> 01:21:33.670
to sort of produce the solutions
or the way forward for problems

01:21:33.670 --> 01:21:38.580
that are no longer, that you
can't solve on a national

01:21:38.580 --> 01:21:41.290
or even the level of
20 states let's say.

01:21:41.290 --> 01:21:47.170
So I would argue that sort of
the task ahead of people who try

01:21:47.170 --> 01:21:52.680
to do this today it's a
tall order and it's not

01:21:52.680 --> 01:21:55.670
that they just sit back, neither
in Brussels nor elsewhere,

01:21:55.670 --> 01:21:58.110
but maybe that's sort of
my own defensive nature

01:21:58.110 --> 01:22:01.640
because I'm part of a
government organization.

01:22:01.640 --> 01:22:02.940
&gt;&gt; Ivan Krastev: You're lazy.

01:22:02.940 --> 01:22:08.030
&gt;&gt; Thomas Bagger: And I
hate to be called lazy, yes.

01:22:08.030 --> 01:22:13.780
The other point is
to the immigration,

01:22:13.780 --> 01:22:17.250
nationalism question,
but it also goes to sort

01:22:17.250 --> 01:22:19.510
of the global capitalism
question.

01:22:19.510 --> 01:22:27.170
You know, clearly Germany is
also experiencing currently a

01:22:27.170 --> 01:22:31.480
repolarization of the
political landscape.

01:22:31.480 --> 01:22:37.180
For decades the pendulum swung
a different direction in Germany

01:22:37.180 --> 01:22:38.630
and in the United States.

01:22:38.630 --> 01:22:43.660
The story I told earlier, when I
was studying here in 1989, 1990,

01:22:43.660 --> 01:22:47.310
this was a very centrist
political discourse,

01:22:47.310 --> 01:22:49.090
very civil in the US.

01:22:49.090 --> 01:22:52.180
It was much more polarized
around the division

01:22:52.180 --> 01:22:54.310
of my country in Germany.

01:22:54.310 --> 01:22:57.160
After unification we became,

01:22:57.160 --> 01:22:59.700
we had a very centrist
political system able

01:22:59.700 --> 01:23:01.770
to integrate the extremes.

01:23:01.770 --> 01:23:04.110
That's why we had grand
coalitions in Germany

01:23:04.110 --> 01:23:08.420
where essentially the former
left and former right party,

01:23:08.420 --> 01:23:10.920
the Christian democrats
and social democrats,

01:23:10.920 --> 01:23:12.420
they could easily
form a coalition

01:23:12.420 --> 01:23:15.180
because they all subscribed
to this general idea

01:23:15.180 --> 01:23:19.470
that you basically just need
the best technocratic solution,

01:23:19.470 --> 01:23:21.490
but there were no big
ideological fights

01:23:21.490 --> 01:23:22.790
to fight anymore.

01:23:22.790 --> 01:23:26.220
Whereas here in the US the
development went exactly the

01:23:26.220 --> 01:23:27.520
other way.

01:23:27.520 --> 01:23:29.060
So now we see a repolarization

01:23:29.060 --> 01:23:31.720
of the German political
landscape and it has a lot to do

01:23:31.720 --> 01:23:35.670
with the immigration question,
with the identity question.

01:23:35.670 --> 01:23:40.210
And I would say that because
both big parties are suffering

01:23:40.210 --> 01:23:45.920
and leading voters to
the polls of the debate.

01:23:45.920 --> 01:23:50.210
But these polls of the debate
that we see are no longer

01:23:50.210 --> 01:23:54.830
in the sort of the classic left,
right spectrum of politics,

01:23:54.830 --> 01:23:57.690
doesn't help you to
understand really anymore.

01:23:57.690 --> 01:24:01.010
It's far more, it's sort
of like a different axis

01:24:01.010 --> 01:24:04.630
that defines open versus closed.

01:24:04.630 --> 01:24:09.660
And if you think about identity
do you think of something

01:24:09.660 --> 01:24:12.790
that you need to protect,
that you need to close off

01:24:12.790 --> 01:24:17.640
against foreigners or others,
those who are not part of it,

01:24:17.640 --> 01:24:19.420
whether that's an
ethnic definition

01:24:19.420 --> 01:24:21.570
or a culturalist definition,

01:24:21.570 --> 01:24:24.290
people who cannot
possibly become part of it?

01:24:24.290 --> 01:24:28.060
Or do you look at identity more
as a resource and says, look,

01:24:28.060 --> 01:24:31.690
this is what Germany has to
offer, for everyone who is able

01:24:31.690 --> 01:24:34.930
to read not just
Goethe or Schiller,

01:24:34.930 --> 01:24:38.060
but listen to German music,
read German intellectuals?

01:24:38.060 --> 01:24:40.220
It's actually an open
resource that can help you

01:24:40.220 --> 01:24:44.360
to relate better to your own
culture, to your own thinking

01:24:44.360 --> 01:24:47.990
about the world, and you have
a much more open perspective.

01:24:47.990 --> 01:24:51.030
And that's what I
see developing,

01:24:51.030 --> 01:24:53.460
that that's the spectrum along

01:24:53.460 --> 01:24:56.350
which political forces
are aligning themselves,

01:24:56.350 --> 01:25:01.910
and clearly also in Germany you
have those that basically want

01:25:01.910 --> 01:25:06.310
to tell sort of the story
of a victim and we need

01:25:06.310 --> 01:25:09.020
to protect ourselves
from attacks from outside

01:25:09.020 --> 01:25:11.750
or from others and from
immigration and so forth.

01:25:11.750 --> 01:25:14.920
And that is what gets me to
the global capitalism question,

01:25:14.920 --> 01:25:17.630
as well, and I think,
Solly, you mentioned it

01:25:17.630 --> 01:25:20.650
in your first statement.

01:25:20.650 --> 01:25:25.060
That sort of our blindness to
the dialectics of globalization,

01:25:25.060 --> 01:25:31.410
to the inequities, to the
incredible loss of credibility

01:25:31.410 --> 01:25:35.200
of the Western model or
the Western order that came

01:25:35.200 --> 01:25:38.280
with the financial
crisis of 2008.

01:25:38.280 --> 01:25:41.600
I mean many of these
other countries,

01:25:41.600 --> 01:25:45.660
they looked at the West
not necessarily with a lot

01:25:45.660 --> 01:25:53.130
of sympathy, but with this idea
that they're richer than we are,

01:25:53.130 --> 01:25:56.290
they also may be freer than
we are, they're more efficient

01:25:56.290 --> 01:25:59.410
than we are, but certainly
they know what they're doing.

01:25:59.410 --> 01:26:02.440
And if not in Iraq with the
Iraq war or in the Middle East

01:26:02.440 --> 01:26:05.030
at least economically
financially they knew what

01:26:05.030 --> 01:26:06.330
they're doing.

01:26:06.330 --> 01:26:10.020
And it turns out we
didn't, and this is not just

01:26:10.020 --> 01:26:12.360
at a state level, but
lots of economic actors

01:26:12.360 --> 01:26:14.060
who were actually
gaming a system

01:26:14.060 --> 01:26:16.210
that they didn't
understand, that they created

01:26:16.210 --> 01:26:18.250
but they couldn't control
and didn't understand,

01:26:18.250 --> 01:26:22.130
with massive repercussions for
lots of other people who tried

01:26:22.130 --> 01:26:25.080
to make a living every
day with their job.

01:26:25.080 --> 01:26:28.760
I think we still underestimate
how much this contributed,

01:26:28.760 --> 01:26:32.290
the 2008 crisis, in the eyes
of the Chinese and the Russians

01:26:32.290 --> 01:26:36.300
and others to say
that's not the future,

01:26:36.300 --> 01:26:37.600
they don't represent the future,

01:26:37.600 --> 01:26:40.800
they don't even know
what they're doing.

01:26:40.800 --> 01:26:49.580
And so I think this question of
what is the role of the state

01:26:49.580 --> 01:26:54.110
in regulating the
affects of globalization,

01:26:54.110 --> 01:26:57.450
what do future trade
agreements have to look like,

01:26:57.450 --> 01:27:05.020
how do we regulate technology
and technological disruptions

01:27:05.020 --> 01:27:07.870
so that it doesn't
destroy the social fabric

01:27:07.870 --> 01:27:11.820
and doesn't only profit a
few globalized companies?

01:27:11.820 --> 01:27:14.330
All of these questions
are back on the agenda,

01:27:14.330 --> 01:27:17.040
and I think there's a
pretty broad consensus now,

01:27:17.040 --> 01:27:22.500
but when you look back
clearly many people were sort

01:27:22.500 --> 01:27:24.860
of oblivious to the challenges

01:27:24.860 --> 01:27:29.820
that globalization was actually
piling up in front of us

01:27:29.820 --> 01:27:34.120
until sort of we, until
we hit the wall with it.

01:27:34.120 --> 01:27:36.330
So in that sense I think
these two are related

01:27:36.330 --> 01:27:41.110
because if you want to keep sort
of the good parts of openness

01:27:41.110 --> 01:27:43.480
as a society, but
also as an economy

01:27:43.480 --> 01:27:45.160
or as a political system,

01:27:45.160 --> 01:27:48.150
because I think we
do need cooperation,

01:27:48.150 --> 01:27:51.320
not just for prosperity but
also for problem solving

01:27:51.320 --> 01:27:54.450
on the international stage, but
then you have to make a case

01:27:54.450 --> 01:27:58.760
that you can do that
also in a just way,

01:27:58.760 --> 01:28:03.100
in a way that satisfy
the largest number.

01:28:03.100 --> 01:28:07.050
And otherwise those who will
argue for a closed system

01:28:07.050 --> 01:28:10.380
and you only look after yourself
and basically everyone is

01:28:10.380 --> 01:28:13.810
out there just to get
the better of you,

01:28:13.810 --> 01:28:15.720
then that will win the day.

01:28:15.720 --> 01:28:20.220
And I think part of the, you
always have this group in each

01:28:20.220 --> 01:28:24.330
and every society, Germany
but also every other country,

01:28:24.330 --> 01:28:29.180
I think the stunning
realization in 2016 in Britain

01:28:29.180 --> 01:28:33.760
or in the US was that that
can actually be enough to take

01:28:33.760 --> 01:28:36.490
over and govern a country.

01:28:36.490 --> 01:28:38.270
&gt;&gt; Ivan Krastev: Rosa?

01:28:38.270 --> 01:28:42.140
&gt;&gt; Rosa Brooks: Yes, let
me start with the question

01:28:42.140 --> 01:28:44.200
of whether the US can
go back to normal?

01:28:44.200 --> 01:28:45.500
What is normal?

01:28:45.500 --> 01:28:48.720
I don't think we
can for two reasons.

01:28:48.720 --> 01:28:52.860
One being that you can't step
into the same river twice,

01:28:52.860 --> 01:28:54.160
it's a different river

01:28:54.160 --> 01:28:58.370
and you're a different person
reason, but also I think

01:28:58.370 --> 01:29:05.010
that the normal was as
we've been saying so full

01:29:05.010 --> 01:29:09.380
of contradictions that we
weren't acknowledging it was an

01:29:09.380 --> 01:29:11.550
unsustainable state of affairs.

01:29:11.550 --> 01:29:15.920
And I see Trump in many
ways less as a cause

01:29:15.920 --> 01:29:18.910
than as a symptom or maybe
it's Trump is the equivalent

01:29:18.910 --> 01:29:21.750
of pouring gasoline on a fire,

01:29:21.750 --> 01:29:24.080
but that fire was
already smoldering,

01:29:24.080 --> 01:29:26.610
it's just that under
Trump it's now a

01:29:26.610 --> 01:29:28.500
full-fledged conflagration.

01:29:28.500 --> 01:29:30.970
But I think even without,
I think all of the forces

01:29:30.970 --> 01:29:32.840
that brought us to
the moment that we're

01:29:32.840 --> 01:29:35.390
in were there before
the election

01:29:35.390 --> 01:29:37.320
of 2016 in the United States.

01:29:37.320 --> 01:29:38.620
We saw them in Europe,

01:29:38.620 --> 01:29:41.020
we saw them in other
parts of the world.

01:29:41.020 --> 01:29:45.880
And I suppose this connects
to the laziness point

01:29:45.880 --> 01:29:51.520
in that I share Solly's
eyerolling

01:29:51.520 --> 01:29:57.080
over the sudden nostalgia and
insistence that we must shore-up

01:29:57.080 --> 01:29:59.910
and preserve the
international liberal order.

01:29:59.910 --> 01:30:03.300
It's like the old quip about the
holy Roman Empire being neither

01:30:03.300 --> 01:30:04.980
holy nor Roman nor an Empire,

01:30:04.980 --> 01:30:06.960
that the international
liberal order it turns

01:30:06.960 --> 01:30:10.180
out was neither entirely
international.

01:30:10.180 --> 01:30:12.290
There were entire
states and peoples

01:30:12.290 --> 01:30:14.340
that were left entirely
out of it.

01:30:14.340 --> 01:30:15.890
Nor was it particularly liberal,

01:30:15.890 --> 01:30:19.260
nor was it very orderly
as it happens.

01:30:19.260 --> 01:30:26.960
And if we are too lazy or
unimaginative or blinded

01:30:26.960 --> 01:30:31.270
to acknowledge that, you
know, that's the first step

01:30:31.270 --> 01:30:32.640
in Alcoholics Anonymous,

01:30:32.640 --> 01:30:34.560
they say the first step
is acknowledging you have

01:30:34.560 --> 01:30:35.860
a problem.

01:30:35.860 --> 01:30:39.110
You know, if we can't even go
that first step and acknowledge

01:30:39.110 --> 01:30:42.460
to ourselves that the
international liberal order was

01:30:42.460 --> 01:30:46.360
never looked like Cary Grant,
to switch to Ivan's metaphor,

01:30:46.360 --> 01:30:50.500
then I don't know how we
go about resolving any

01:30:50.500 --> 01:30:53.310
of those internal
contradictions.

01:30:53.310 --> 01:30:57.360
And I was reminded when you
were talking of my favorite,

01:30:57.360 --> 01:30:59.870
of the role that, as you say,

01:30:59.870 --> 01:31:04.130
the United States played a
significant role in undermining,

01:31:04.130 --> 01:31:07.750
in making sure that that
order would not be fully

01:31:07.750 --> 01:31:10.130
international, liberal
or orderly

01:31:10.130 --> 01:31:12.240
through actions such
as the Iraq war.

01:31:12.240 --> 01:31:14.440
I was reminded of one of
my favorite Putin quotes,

01:31:14.440 --> 01:31:16.490
which I think I quoted
to my friends

01:31:16.490 --> 01:31:21.280
in the hypocrisy study
group on previous occasions.

01:31:21.280 --> 01:31:26.630
Vladimir Putin always
quotable when, and this was not

01:31:26.630 --> 01:31:30.980
over the Iraq war, but when
Kosovo declared independence

01:31:30.980 --> 01:31:34.650
unilaterally and, of course, the
United States along with most

01:31:34.650 --> 01:31:39.100
of the EU states had said, no,
no, no, Russia, don't worry,

01:31:39.100 --> 01:31:42.000
we are not going to support
Kosovo independence from Serbia,

01:31:42.000 --> 01:31:45.480
absolutely not, we support
Serbian sovereignty, et cetera.

01:31:45.480 --> 01:31:47.410
And then when Kosovo
unilaterally declared

01:31:47.410 --> 01:31:50.940
independence and the EU and the
United States immediately said,

01:31:50.940 --> 01:31:53.350
okay, we recognize
Kosovo independence,

01:31:53.350 --> 01:31:56.190
Vladimir Putin said something,
this is not a direct quote

01:31:56.190 --> 01:31:58.530
but it was more or
less along these lines,

01:31:58.530 --> 01:32:01.530
he said you Americans,
you Europeans,

01:32:01.530 --> 01:32:04.280
those of you recognizing
Kosovo's independence,

01:32:04.280 --> 01:32:07.760
you do not understand, you
are overturning 200 years

01:32:07.760 --> 01:32:10.430
of international norms
about sovereignty

01:32:10.430 --> 01:32:13.560
and you do not understand
this is a two-sided stick

01:32:13.560 --> 01:32:16.830
and the other end will come
back and hit you in the face.

01:32:16.830 --> 01:32:20.110
And, of course, a few
years later in Crimea

01:32:20.110 --> 01:32:23.220
that stick did come back
and hit us in the face,

01:32:23.220 --> 01:32:28.230
and he wasn't wrong to
level that critique.

01:32:28.230 --> 01:32:32.380
It does, one of the things that
depresses me most is I do think

01:32:32.380 --> 01:32:34.740
that in this country, we've
been talking about this

01:32:34.740 --> 01:32:37.320
with our friend and
colleague, Steve Walt,

01:32:37.320 --> 01:32:41.080
one thing that depresses me
most is the I think inability

01:32:41.080 --> 01:32:44.270
of the sort of mainstream
foreign policy elites

01:32:44.270 --> 01:32:47.760
and also Democratic Party
elites to grapple with any

01:32:47.760 --> 01:32:49.060
of those contradictions.

01:32:49.060 --> 01:32:50.980
And it pains me to say

01:32:50.980 --> 01:32:53.010
that I still see these
statements coming

01:32:53.010 --> 01:32:57.090
out of my favorite
Washington liberal think tanks

01:32:57.090 --> 01:33:01.060
and organizations where
you'll get this sort

01:33:01.060 --> 01:33:04.350
of unblushing contradictions
where you'll sort

01:33:04.350 --> 01:33:06.980
of simultaneously
say we recognize

01:33:06.980 --> 01:33:10.200
that endless war is not good for
our nation and so we will work

01:33:10.200 --> 01:33:14.010
to end these wars, we recognize
that terrorism is a scourge

01:33:14.010 --> 01:33:16.320
to the whole world and so
we will pursue terrorists

01:33:16.320 --> 01:33:17.620
to the end of the earth.

01:33:17.620 --> 01:33:19.640
And you think wait a
second, hold on, you know,

01:33:19.640 --> 01:33:21.650
how are you going to
do both of those things

01:33:21.650 --> 01:33:23.990
because if you think both of
those, that's not going to work.

01:33:23.990 --> 01:33:29.480
And yet I think that we are
still lazy or still blinded,

01:33:29.480 --> 01:33:33.310
there is a fantasy that
there is a sustainable normal

01:33:33.310 --> 01:33:36.470
that we can simply
revert to and just edit

01:33:36.470 --> 01:33:40.220
out this whole business of
Trump and this whole nationalism

01:33:40.220 --> 01:33:44.050
and populism business
and it really isn't.

01:33:45.960 --> 01:33:48.890
The final question I think and
I'm sure I'm missing several,

01:33:48.890 --> 01:33:54.140
but about young people and
how do we educate young people

01:33:54.140 --> 01:33:57.680
to not be quite as hypocritical
and not be quite as lazy?

01:33:57.680 --> 01:34:00.780
I almost worry, and I
have two teenaged children

01:34:00.780 --> 01:34:04.200
and I watch them, that
they are so deeply aware

01:34:04.200 --> 01:34:07.550
of American hypocrisy that I
worry it becomes paralyzing.

01:34:07.550 --> 01:34:12.940
You know, that they do not think
of the United States as a force

01:34:12.940 --> 01:34:16.690
for global good, they
think of the US as a force

01:34:16.690 --> 01:34:18.870
for global disruption
and inequality,

01:34:18.870 --> 01:34:21.980
and of course they're
right to think that,

01:34:21.980 --> 01:34:24.530
but I do worry a little bit
that that leads to a sort

01:34:24.530 --> 01:34:26.500
of sense of paralysis.

01:34:26.500 --> 01:34:30.750
It's not laziness, it's
depression, it's a sense of, oh,

01:34:30.750 --> 01:34:35.740
well, we're out of big
ideas, communism didn't work,

01:34:35.740 --> 01:34:37.750
the great American
experiment didn't work,

01:34:37.750 --> 01:34:40.890
the international liberal order
wasn't so liberal or orderly,

01:34:40.890 --> 01:34:42.680
you know, we're out of ideas.

01:34:42.680 --> 01:34:49.330
And I don't quite know how
to urge them and urge others

01:34:49.330 --> 01:34:52.290
in their generation,
urge the students I teach

01:34:52.290 --> 01:34:56.630
to say don't give
up, don't be lazy,

01:34:56.630 --> 01:35:00.850
but don't stop being
creative and imaginative

01:35:00.850 --> 01:35:02.190
or then we really are done.

01:35:02.190 --> 01:35:05.710
And if there is a bright
side to Donald Trump

01:35:05.710 --> 01:35:10.170
and the various other Trump-like
conflagrations that we're seeing

01:35:10.170 --> 01:35:12.420
around the globe
today, you know,

01:35:12.420 --> 01:35:16.540
it's the old saying what does
not kill us makes us strong.

01:35:16.540 --> 01:35:18.430
If this doesn't completely
blow things

01:35:18.430 --> 01:35:22.990
up I think it does create some
potential space for people

01:35:22.990 --> 01:35:26.760
to break out of those old
left, right dichotomies

01:35:26.760 --> 01:35:29.660
because they have
proven inadequate.

01:35:29.660 --> 01:35:33.220
And I hope, I love to see
young people viewing this more

01:35:33.220 --> 01:35:37.020
as a clarion call
to say, all right,

01:35:37.020 --> 01:35:41.510
those old ideas did not
work, what's the next set

01:35:41.510 --> 01:35:43.660
of big ideas, and that's going

01:35:43.660 --> 01:35:46.700
to be your job to
figure them out.

01:35:46.700 --> 01:35:48.930
&gt;&gt; Robert Cooper: I
think I would rather go

01:35:48.930 --> 01:35:52.400
for little ideas actually.

01:35:52.400 --> 01:35:56.910
I think the big ideas are the
ones that get us into trouble.

01:35:56.910 --> 01:36:00.040
But I think that the
world can be made better,

01:36:00.040 --> 01:36:03.380
but I think that it's mostly
made better bit by bit.

01:36:03.380 --> 01:36:07.370
And I think that the US played
an absolutely fantastic,

01:36:07.370 --> 01:36:10.330
stunning, indispensable
role in that

01:36:10.330 --> 01:36:13.950
and one ought to remember that.

01:36:13.950 --> 01:36:19.070
You can see it, if you have
to and now there are lots of,

01:36:19.070 --> 01:36:22.710
and when the US makes mistakes
it makes gigantic mistakes.

01:36:22.710 --> 01:36:27.470
My personal view has always been
that the first duty of Europe is

01:36:27.470 --> 01:36:29.810
to stop the US from doing
really stupid things,

01:36:29.810 --> 01:36:34.080
and that's why actually it
would be better if the UK was

01:36:34.080 --> 01:36:39.380
in the EU because,
but still I would --

01:36:39.380 --> 01:36:43.790
if you're European you can't
forget how the US handled

01:36:43.790 --> 01:36:47.570
post-war Europe, it's
actually a miracle.

01:36:47.570 --> 01:36:52.530
So maybe I can just answer
one or two of the other?

01:36:52.530 --> 01:36:54.390
&gt;&gt; Solly Roselle: I
wanted to add one sentence.

01:36:54.390 --> 01:36:59.510
You did mention getting
into EU I think at 90 some.

01:36:59.510 --> 01:37:05.980
And I think what he says that
is important for the next thing,

01:37:05.980 --> 01:37:09.970
we're still in the
era of Ronald Reagan,

01:37:09.970 --> 01:37:12.420
that is government
is not the solution,

01:37:12.420 --> 01:37:14.500
government is the problem.

01:37:14.500 --> 01:37:17.950
And what Paul Walker
was saying was we have

01:37:17.950 --> 01:37:22.160
to make public service
valuable again.

01:37:22.160 --> 01:37:25.050
That is in my view
part of the answer.

01:37:25.050 --> 01:37:27.440
I just wanted to add that.

01:37:27.440 --> 01:37:28.740
&gt;&gt; Ivan Krastev:
Robert, just I come back

01:37:28.740 --> 01:37:33.300
because I have it stuck
in my head, in 19 --

01:37:33.300 --> 01:37:37.610
I'm not very good at
the dates, it's in 1943

01:37:37.610 --> 01:37:38.910
or something like that.

01:37:38.910 --> 01:37:40.870
&gt;&gt; 20th Century.

01:37:40.870 --> 01:37:42.420
&gt;&gt; Ivan Krastev: 20th Century.

01:37:42.420 --> 01:37:53.570
&gt;&gt; Anyway, I wasn't yet, but
still in 1943 the German who was

01:37:53.570 --> 01:37:58.960
in charge of running Denmark
as an occupied territory

01:37:58.960 --> 01:38:01.520
in World War II received
an instruction

01:38:01.520 --> 01:38:05.200
to solve the Jewish question.

01:38:06.550 --> 01:38:12.800
He almost certainly knew
that the third secretary

01:38:12.800 --> 01:38:16.530
in the German Embassy, George
Dukfitz [assumed spelling],

01:38:16.530 --> 01:38:21.980
was going to inform
the community leaders

01:38:21.980 --> 01:38:24.590
in Denmark what was coming.

01:38:24.590 --> 01:38:26.220
And so when the Gestapo arrived

01:38:26.220 --> 01:38:30.630
to arrest the Jews
they found only 200.

01:38:30.630 --> 01:38:36.190
Well, that was 200 too
many, but the rest escaped.

01:38:36.190 --> 01:38:40.880
And the reason why, it's
not absolutely clear,

01:38:40.880 --> 01:38:43.540
and I forget his name, whether
the man who was in charge

01:38:43.540 --> 01:38:48.670
of Denmark at the time
told Dukfitz to do this

01:38:48.670 --> 01:38:51.680
but I'm pretty sure that he
guessed what was happening.

01:38:51.680 --> 01:38:55.680
And the reason why was because
over the horizon they could see

01:38:55.680 --> 01:38:57.440
the US coming.

01:38:57.440 --> 01:39:00.780
And the guess that you made at
the point that this order went

01:39:00.780 --> 01:39:03.280
out was you guessed that the US,

01:39:03.280 --> 01:39:07.290
that the world was probably
going to be a liberal world.

01:39:07.290 --> 01:39:12.090
And, well, he got a lot of
debits on his balance sheet

01:39:12.090 --> 01:39:16.500
and he wanted to try and
finish with one credit.

01:39:16.500 --> 01:39:20.600
And I think that it was even
the looming presence of the US

01:39:20.600 --> 01:39:23.410
at that stage in the war
was a good influence,

01:39:23.410 --> 01:39:25.470
and there's much,
much more behind that.

01:39:25.470 --> 01:39:26.860
So that's just intervention

01:39:26.860 --> 01:39:28.910
because it happened
to be in my head.

01:39:28.910 --> 01:39:31.440
But I want just to come back
to one or two of the questions.

01:39:31.440 --> 01:39:35.530
First of all, the
mention of the IMF,

01:39:35.530 --> 01:39:37.210
I think the IMF is
an interesting case

01:39:37.210 --> 01:39:41.040
because the IMF was set-up
to do, to manage a system

01:39:41.040 --> 01:39:42.760
which is completely
different from the one

01:39:42.760 --> 01:39:45.040
that we have at the moment.

01:39:45.040 --> 01:39:48.080
And you thought that this
system was being destroyed

01:39:48.080 --> 01:39:52.020
with the Nixon chalk, as
they called it in Japan.

01:39:52.020 --> 01:39:54.510
Actually it's not a bad thing

01:39:54.510 --> 01:39:58.140
that we have a serious
international institution

01:39:58.140 --> 01:40:02.500
that has some responsibility,
rather vague,

01:40:02.500 --> 01:40:05.170
for the international
financial system.

01:40:05.170 --> 01:40:07.440
It's not exactly a
lender of last resort,

01:40:07.440 --> 01:40:10.660
that's Wall Street is the lender
of last resort, but the ability

01:40:10.660 --> 01:40:15.800
to cooperate in financial crises
and the ability of the IMF

01:40:15.800 --> 01:40:18.470
to steady national
crises and to deal,

01:40:18.470 --> 01:40:22.130
to help Wall Street
basically at the moment deal

01:40:22.130 --> 01:40:24.610
with real international crises.

01:40:24.610 --> 01:40:26.870
I think that that's
actually indispensable

01:40:26.870 --> 01:40:28.380
for the order at the moment.

01:40:28.380 --> 01:40:33.490
So it wasn't what they
planned at Brettenwoods,

01:40:33.490 --> 01:40:38.370
but it's I think still a very,
very valuable institution.

01:40:38.370 --> 01:40:41.620
It makes mistakes like others
do, but learns like others do.

01:40:41.620 --> 01:40:44.390
It's a good thing about
institutions, unlike men,

01:40:44.390 --> 01:40:47.060
is that they sometimes learn.

01:40:47.060 --> 01:40:49.580
Second, a remark on languages.

01:40:49.580 --> 01:40:54.000
The British Ambassador
in Tehran,

01:40:54.000 --> 01:40:57.330
way back when the
Shah was there,

01:40:57.330 --> 01:41:00.390
said that when a British
Minister came to call

01:41:00.390 --> 01:41:05.550
on the Shah and the Shah spoke
English, which he did perfectly,

01:41:05.550 --> 01:41:07.650
it made his blood run cold

01:41:07.650 --> 01:41:11.570
because the British Minister
would think he was dealing

01:41:11.570 --> 01:41:15.520
with an English gentleman,
whereas, he was actually dealing

01:41:15.520 --> 01:41:19.240
with somebody who was very
complicated and very different

01:41:19.240 --> 01:41:23.200
from the way in which he
seemed when he spoke English.

01:41:23.200 --> 01:41:27.350
Consequently, there's
a lot to be said for,

01:41:27.350 --> 01:41:30.990
actually there's a lot to
be said for interpreters,

01:41:30.990 --> 01:41:33.690
at least you know then
that you're dealing

01:41:33.690 --> 01:41:34.990
with a foreign culture

01:41:34.990 --> 01:41:38.820
and foreigners are not
necessarily exactly the same

01:41:38.820 --> 01:41:40.120
as you.

01:41:40.120 --> 01:41:46.830
So it's a pity that American
Presidents don't speak however

01:41:46.830 --> 01:41:52.700
many languages that are left,
but it's several thousand.

01:41:52.700 --> 01:41:54.230
But, well, they have diplomats

01:41:54.230 --> 01:41:56.260
and other people
who can help them.

01:41:56.260 --> 01:42:00.000
But one should never forget
that it's not just the language,

01:42:00.000 --> 01:42:03.790
even if the language is the
same the ways of thinking

01:42:03.790 --> 01:42:06.850
and the history and the
words, they're all different.

01:42:06.850 --> 01:42:09.440
And then I come back to
the question that was kind

01:42:09.440 --> 01:42:13.490
of in away for me, which
is a complicated one.

01:42:13.490 --> 01:42:15.340
Theresa May, wow.

01:42:15.340 --> 01:42:22.090
The demonstration I was at
last weekend there was somebody

01:42:22.090 --> 01:42:26.940
carrying a sign saying,
hey, hey, Theresa May,

01:42:26.940 --> 01:42:29.720
when will you let
us have our say?

01:42:29.720 --> 01:42:33.020
This recalls the last
demonstration I went

01:42:33.020 --> 01:42:35.550
on which was against
the Vietnam war,

01:42:35.550 --> 01:42:40.800
in between I'd missed
the demonstrations, but.

01:42:40.800 --> 01:42:42.570
&gt;&gt; Ivan Krastev:
Being in office.

01:42:42.570 --> 01:42:44.930
&gt;&gt; Robert Cooper: Yes,
Theresa May was never planned

01:42:44.930 --> 01:42:52.050
to be Prime Minister and
she was not intended by God

01:42:52.050 --> 01:42:58.130
to be Prime Minister, but things
sometimes turn out that way.

01:42:58.130 --> 01:43:00.620
And when she became
Prime Minister she knew

01:43:00.620 --> 01:43:04.070
that she'd voted
for the other side,

01:43:04.070 --> 01:43:06.920
but the first thing she
thought she'd better do is

01:43:06.920 --> 01:43:10.510
to persuade the BREXITers
that she was one of them.

01:43:10.510 --> 01:43:13.060
So she made some fire
breathing speeches

01:43:13.060 --> 01:43:16.410
about how awful the European
Union was and said we were going

01:43:16.410 --> 01:43:20.460
to leave absolutely everything
that we could possibly leave.

01:43:20.460 --> 01:43:22.470
Actually she didn't
really know very much

01:43:22.470 --> 01:43:24.980
about the European
Union at that point.

01:43:24.980 --> 01:43:27.540
Nobody does, it's
only when you leave it

01:43:27.540 --> 01:43:29.570
that you begin to understand it.

01:43:29.570 --> 01:43:31.540
&gt;&gt; Ivan Krastev:
Like divorce, yes.

01:43:31.540 --> 01:43:33.940
&gt;&gt; Robert Cooper:
Exactly, exactly.

01:43:33.940 --> 01:43:36.870
She's been on this
voyage of discovery.

01:43:36.870 --> 01:43:41.250
Everybody should, they say
no good marriage is complete

01:43:41.250 --> 01:43:44.350
without one.

01:43:44.350 --> 01:43:47.440
So everybody ought to try
and do a mock divorce early

01:43:47.440 --> 01:43:50.620
on in their marriage and then
they would realize what they

01:43:50.620 --> 01:43:53.190
were going to lose.

01:43:53.190 --> 01:43:55.730
And she knew about one
specific sector quite well

01:43:55.730 --> 01:43:57.560
and she operated it
quite efficiently,

01:43:57.560 --> 01:44:01.150
it's a very narrow sector
concerned with things

01:44:01.150 --> 01:44:04.100
like European arrest warrant
and very useful instruments

01:44:04.100 --> 01:44:05.620
but a very narrow sector.

01:44:05.620 --> 01:44:07.220
And she's been discovering
all kinds

01:44:07.220 --> 01:44:09.270
of things she didn't
know before,

01:44:09.270 --> 01:44:14.750
like about how a supply
chain works and the problems

01:44:14.750 --> 01:44:16.050
of the Irish border,

01:44:16.050 --> 01:44:17.710
all of these things
that she didn't know.

01:44:17.710 --> 01:44:24.310
And I didn't know, too, even
though I worked 10 years.

01:44:24.310 --> 01:44:31.030
The other thing that she's
learning is she's learning how

01:44:31.030 --> 01:44:34.250
extraordinarily difficult
it is, first of all,

01:44:34.250 --> 01:44:37.230
it's extraordinarily difficult
to negotiate with somebody

01:44:37.230 --> 01:44:39.380
if you don't know what you want.

01:44:39.380 --> 01:44:45.900
And her opening slogan of no
deal is better than a bad deal,

01:44:45.900 --> 01:44:48.230
she didn't know what
she meant by a bad deal

01:44:48.230 --> 01:44:50.410
and she certainly
didn't know what, quotes,

01:44:50.410 --> 01:44:52.030
no deal was going to mean.

01:44:52.030 --> 01:44:54.240
So this was completely vacuous

01:44:54.240 --> 01:44:59.660
and you can't govern
just by slogans.

01:44:59.660 --> 01:45:03.700
And now as the more
she discovers,

01:45:03.700 --> 01:45:08.370
the more she discovers what is
disaster leaving the European

01:45:08.370 --> 01:45:11.970
Union, potentially is for the
UK, and the more she's trying

01:45:11.970 --> 01:45:13.830
to find ways around it.

01:45:13.830 --> 01:45:16.530
But she's also discovering
that negotiating

01:45:16.530 --> 01:45:20.690
with the European Union
is one definition of hell,

01:45:20.690 --> 01:45:23.480
and negotiating with
the European Union

01:45:23.480 --> 01:45:26.620
on absolutely everything and
all things that are vital

01:45:26.620 --> 01:45:30.650
to your country is about as bad
as you can get in terms of hell.

01:45:30.650 --> 01:45:33.530
It's the seventh
circle, or I don't know

01:45:33.530 --> 01:45:39.880
which way the circles go,
anyway it's the hottest part.

01:45:39.880 --> 01:45:42.810
And so it would have been better

01:45:42.810 --> 01:45:45.900
if the UK hadn't
started the process

01:45:45.900 --> 01:45:48.210
without knowing what it wanted

01:45:48.210 --> 01:45:50.880
and how it was going
to get there.

01:45:50.880 --> 01:45:55.550
But the point about the European
Union is it creates fantastic

01:45:55.550 --> 01:45:59.330
solidarity among the
member states because,

01:45:59.330 --> 01:46:06.400
as I think someone said earlier,
I think it was probably Thomas,

01:46:06.400 --> 01:46:10.270
you're always going to need
somebody else's help the next

01:46:10.270 --> 01:46:13.890
day, you can never afford
to break with everybody.

01:46:13.890 --> 01:46:16.590
So if somebody has got
a problem that matters

01:46:16.590 --> 01:46:20.100
to them then you really
take it into account,

01:46:20.100 --> 01:46:22.180
you mold your policy around it.

01:46:22.180 --> 01:46:25.460
The Irish care very, very deeply

01:46:25.460 --> 01:46:27.860
about the Irish border
for very good reason.

01:46:27.860 --> 01:46:32.510
The European Union will not
budge from supporting Ireland

01:46:32.510 --> 01:46:36.280
because it's a member,
it's one of them.

01:46:36.280 --> 01:46:39.910
So for the first time in
history we have Dublin,

01:46:39.910 --> 01:46:41.890
which used to be
kicked around by London

01:46:41.890 --> 01:46:44.900
because it was just a
rather difficult colony,

01:46:44.900 --> 01:46:49.910
we have Dublin dictating
the terms to London.

01:46:49.910 --> 01:46:55.030
The European Union is anybody
who wants anything now,

01:46:55.030 --> 01:46:57.020
and the Spanish were talking

01:46:57.020 --> 01:46:58.890
about whether they might
get Gibraltar back,

01:46:58.890 --> 01:47:00.720
I'm not sure how we fix that,

01:47:00.720 --> 01:47:04.420
but anybody in the European
Union who wants something

01:47:04.420 --> 01:47:08.650
from Britain is now in
position to demand it.

01:47:08.650 --> 01:47:11.410
So this is the most
awful negotiation

01:47:11.410 --> 01:47:15.000
that you can imagine, and
the most sensible thing

01:47:15.000 --> 01:47:18.140
to do would be to give
up the whole idea.

01:47:18.140 --> 01:47:22.120
So I think that's probably
a good place to stop.

01:47:22.120 --> 01:47:24.450
&gt;&gt; Thomas Bagger:
Can I have a --

01:47:24.450 --> 01:47:29.080
just because Robert was kind
enough to bring up the case

01:47:29.080 --> 01:47:31.350
of Dukfitz who saved the lives

01:47:31.350 --> 01:47:37.430
of 7,000 Danish Jews 75 years
ago and it brought me back

01:47:37.430 --> 01:47:39.430
to your question
about education.

01:47:39.430 --> 01:47:44.370
The way I tell this story
of the last 30 years to me

01:47:44.370 --> 01:47:47.960
and my own sort of illusions,
intellectual illusions

01:47:47.960 --> 01:47:52.140
about grand convergence and
the end of history is also

01:47:52.140 --> 01:47:55.780
to realize that in
reality the future is open

01:47:55.780 --> 01:47:58.670
and that we should be aware
of the grand generalization.

01:47:58.670 --> 01:48:01.780
So I'm very much with you
on sort of little steps

01:48:01.780 --> 01:48:06.250
to make the world better,
but I like the Dukfitz' case

01:48:06.250 --> 01:48:10.050
because I don't think he did
it because he was concerned

01:48:10.050 --> 01:48:13.590
about a world dominated
by America in the future.

01:48:13.590 --> 01:48:15.930
I think he did it because
he knew it was wrong

01:48:15.930 --> 01:48:19.420
if it went ahead, he knew
what was coming and he decided

01:48:19.420 --> 01:48:22.360
that he was in a position,
he knew the right people

01:48:22.360 --> 01:48:26.380
to actually open a door for
these 7,000 people to escape

01:48:26.380 --> 01:48:28.720
to Sweden across
the narrow waterway

01:48:28.720 --> 01:48:31.680
between Denmark and Sweden.

01:48:31.680 --> 01:48:34.060
And what that story
really tells in the midst

01:48:34.060 --> 01:48:38.860
of very dark times is
individuals matter,

01:48:38.860 --> 01:48:42.310
people matter, they
can change the world.

01:48:42.310 --> 01:48:46.070
And I think that would
be the fallacy from sort

01:48:46.070 --> 01:48:50.490
of saying farewell to the
grand generalization of 1989,

01:48:50.490 --> 01:48:53.350
that the future is sort of
predetermined, only to turn

01:48:53.350 --> 01:48:56.130
around and say, well,
we were too optimistic,

01:48:56.130 --> 01:48:58.270
now the world belongs
to the strong man

01:48:58.270 --> 01:49:00.250
or to the authoritarian system.

01:49:00.250 --> 01:49:02.450
None of that is predetermined
either,

01:49:02.450 --> 01:49:06.400
so it actually does matter
what you're interested in,

01:49:06.400 --> 01:49:09.540
which position you're in, and
what you do with the space

01:49:09.540 --> 01:49:11.060
that is accorded to you.

01:49:11.060 --> 01:49:14.880
And I think that's actually
quite an optimistic outcome

01:49:14.880 --> 01:49:16.180
for me.

01:49:16.180 --> 01:49:21.750
So my, I would say be curious
and aspire to something.

01:49:21.750 --> 01:49:23.940
&gt;&gt; Robert Cooper: And you never
know when you may get the chance

01:49:23.940 --> 01:49:25.240
to make some decisive decision.

01:49:25.240 --> 01:49:26.540
&gt;&gt; Thomas Bagger: We
all don't know, yes,

01:49:26.540 --> 01:49:30.150
and that may be a test
but it also may be a way

01:49:30.150 --> 01:49:33.290
to prove yourself and
actually make the world better.

01:49:33.290 --> 01:49:36.360
&gt;&gt; Ivan Krastev: History does
not end, but the panels do.

01:49:36.360 --> 01:49:40.570
And I want very much to thank
you, and I really do believe

01:49:40.570 --> 01:49:43.420
that people matter, even
people on the panel matter.

01:49:43.420 --> 01:49:44.720
So thank them.

01:49:44.720 --> 01:49:46.600
Thank you very much and
thanks to The Kluge Center.

